{This lecture will feature the most important structure that every QGA player
should know - the isolated queen's pawn. This structure arises in the systems
with e2-e3. Even though the IQP can be a topic of an entire book, I will try
to summarize the most important ideas. We will take a look at the structure
from the perspective of the Queen's Gambit Accepted. Besides the positional
overview, I will try to provide a solid base for your opening repertoire. The
most important position of the lecture arises after} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e3
Nf6 4. Nf3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O {Now, instead of the most popular 6...a6, I
prove that the straightforward} cxd4 7. exd4 Be7 8. Nc3 O-O {is playable as
well. By immediately taking on d4, Black rules out all the annoying systems
based on dxc5. On the other hand, in the arising IQP position, White enjoys a
lot of freedom. He can choose among various attacking setups. In the lecture,
I should how Black should fight against the following ideas: 1) Setups with
Bg5 2) The battery Bc2+Qd3 3) Setups with Qe2 and Rd1 4) Ideas based on d4-d5
In the article I discuss the following strategies: 1) Simplification 2)
Pressure on the isolated pawn 3) Transition into a symmetrical pawn structure.
At the beginning of the lecture, you will see which typical endgame positions
we should avoid and what is our dream endgame scenario. I hope that after
studying the lecture, you will also improve your general chess understanding.}
*

