{[%evp 0,102,24,26,28,-3,9,9,28,24,24,46,44,49,68,49,31,49,49,45,49,45,64,2,2,
17,28,20,48,31,31,31,31,31,31,31,31,31,31,31,41,-20,9,9,11,12,12,12,12,19,19,
19,19,44,1,-3,60,41,52,3,72,57,68,86,97,91,94,46,36,35,35,26,26,22,77,77,78,78,
78,78,61,65,73,65,77,36,77,62,62,-107,-103,-103,-103,-103,-103,-224,-231,-253,
-210,-285,-216,-230,-238,-1271,-1276] At the beginning, we shall take a look
at a few examples featuring the advance d4-d5. After analyzing many positions,
I can say that this advance can be dangerous only White has a significant
advantage in the development or considerably more active pieces.} 1. d4 d5 2.
c4 e6 3. Nf3 dxc4 4. e3 Nf6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O cxd4 {Surprisingly, this line
with early capture on d4 turns out to be easy to handle and very solid.} 7.
exd4 Be7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Re1 Nc6 10. a3 {The main idea of this move is to
prevent the manoeuvre...Nb4-d5. Also, under favourable circumstances, White
can set up the battery Bc2+Qd3.} b6 {Developing the light-squared bishop
should be our first priority.} 11. Bg5 Bb7 12. Qd3 {[%cal Ga1d1,Gc4a2,Ga2b1]
White is planning to proceed with Rad1 followed by Ba2-b1. In order to release
tension, Black should exchange some pieces.} h6 $1 {This is the right move
order. Before playing ...Nh5, we should force the bishop to h4.} ({The
immediate} 12... Nh5 {can be met with} 13. Bd2 {when it's not clear what
exactly the black knight is doing on h5.}) 13. Bf4 {White prefers to keep the
bishop on the diagonal c1-h6 in order to make use of the advance ...h7-h6.} ({
The thematic reaction to} 13. Bh4 {would be} Nh5 {when White cannot prevent
further exchanges. For example, after} 14. Bxe7 Nxe7 {[%cal Gh5f6,Gd8d6,Gf8d8]
Black is ready to proceed with ...Nf6 followed by ...Qd6 and ...Rfd8, thus
putting up tremendous pressure on d4.}) 13... Bd6 $1 {Black keeps insisting on
exchanging pieces. Additionally, the e7-square is now available for the knight.
At this point, Dubov decided to force matters by means of} 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. d5
{As we have already pointed out, this advance works only when there is a
significant difference in the activity or development.} exd5 16. Nxd5 Nxd5 17.
Bxd5 Rad8 $11 {The position is equal. Later on, Dubov failed to create any
problems for his opponent.} 18. Rad1 Qf6 19. Qe4 Rd7 20. h4 g6 21. Rc1 Re7 22.
Qa4 Rxe1+ 23. Rxe1 Rd8 24. Qe4 Qd6 25. Rd1 Kg7 26. Rd2 Qf6 27. g4 g5 (27... Ne5
28. Nxe5 Rxd5 29. Rxd5 Qe6 $11) 28. hxg5 hxg5 29. Qe3 Kh6 (29... Qf4 30. Qxf4
gxf4 $11) 30. Bxc6 Bxc6 31. Nxg5 Kg6 32. Ne4 Qe7 33. f4 Bxe4 34. Rxd8 Qxd8 35.
Qxe4+ Kg7 36. f5 Qd1+ 37. Kf2 Qd2+ 38. Qe2 Qf4+ 39. Kg2 Kh6 40. Kh3 f6 41. Kh4
a5 42. b3 Qc1 43. a4 Qf4 44. Qb2 Qg5+ 45. Kg3 Qe3+ 46. Kg2 Kg5 47. b4 Qe4+ 48.
Kf2 Qxb4 49. Qe2 Qxg4 50. Qe8 Qxf5+ 51. Kg3 Qe5+ 0-1

