-116,-117,-124,-145,-153,-162,-159,-154,-154,-185,-195,-205,-231,-208,-208,
-263,-309,-579,-619,-29999,-30000] The same line in a slightly different
version was seen in the game Van Foreest, L - Anton Guijarro, D.} 1. e4 c6 2.
d4 d5 {Even though Black played the Caro-Kann, we will get exactly the same
QGA type of position.} 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3 e6 6. Nf3 dxc4 7. Bxc4 Be7
8. O-O O-O 9. Re1 Nc6 10. a3 b6 11. d5 {Now, we have exactly the same line as
in the game Fedoseev, V - Paravyan, D. This time, however, Black employed the
correct move order -} Na5 12. Ba2 Nxd5 13. Nxd5 exd5 14. Qxd5 {White hopes
that after the exchange of the queens, Black will face difficulties
coordinating his pieces.} ({As we have seen, after} 14. Bxd5 Bb7 {Black has
nothing to worry about.}) 14... Be6 $1 {This is the correct reaction. Black's
piece activity provides more than enough compensation for the slightly weak
e6-pawn.} 15. Qxd8 Raxd8 16. Bxe6 fxe6 17. b4 {White should already find a
precise way to equalize.} ({After the forced sequence} 17. Rxe6 $6 Rd1+ 18. Re1
Rxe1+ 19. Nxe1 Rd8 20. Be3 Bf6 21. Rb1 Nc4 $15 {Black's advantage is out of
question.}) 17... Bf6 18. Rb1 $6 {This passive move creates problems for White.
} ({Better would have been} 18. Ra2 Nc4 19. Bg5 $11 {with equality.}) 18... Nc4
{Even though White can still make a draw, practically speaking, Black is
obviously better. Later on, he managed to win.} 19. a4 Rd3 20. Rxe6 Na3 21.
Bxa3 Rxa3 22. b5 Rxa4 23. Rc6 Ra2 24. Rc7 Re8 25. g3 Ree2 26. Re1 Rxe1+ 27.
Nxe1 Bd4 28. Nc2 Bc5 29. Ne3 h5 30. Nf5 g6 31. Ne7+ Kf7 32. Nc6+ Ke6 33. Nxa7
Bxf2+ 34. Kf1 Bc5 35. Rc6+ Kf5 36. Nc8 Rf2+ 37. Ke1 Rxh2 38. Nxb6 Bf2+ 39. Kf1
Bxg3 40. Nd5 g5 41. Ne3+ Ke4 42. Ng2 h4 43. Rc4+ Kd3 44. Rg4 Rh1# 0-1

