{[%evp 0,60,25,14,14,-6,13,0,28,42,39,31,45,46,54,44,52,42,46,34,23,24,39,12,
97,20,3,10,10,-23,-18,-56,-21,-26,-16,-63,-33,-42,-24,-24,-19,-12,0,0,23,0,0,
-71,-84,-109,-101,-103,-99,-94,-90,-120,0,0,5,10,22,-77,-35] Now, we shall
take a look at several examples where Black manages to put strong pressure on
the isolated pawn. In this game, White lost easily, mainly due to his passive
play. Everything until move 12 is already known to us.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3.
Nf3 dxc4 4. e3 Nf6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O cxd4 7. exd4 Be7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Bg5 Nc6 10.
Re1 h6 11. Bh4 Nh5 12. Bg3 {White grants the bishop pair to his opponent but
tries to reduce Black's control of the d5-square. Black immediately started
putting pressure on d4 by means of} Nxg3 13. hxg3 Bf6 14. Ne2 $6 {This passive
move gives Black a huge advantage.} ({White should have played} 14. d5 Bxc3 15.
bxc3 Na5 16. Bd3 exd5 17. Bc2 $44 {when his compensation is enough for a draw.}
) 14... Qb6 15. Qd3 Rd8 $6 {I mark this move as dubious only for the sake of
objectivity. In a blitz game, however, it's very difficult to realize that the
other rook should go to d8.} ({More precise would have been} 15... Bd7 16. Rad1
Rad8 {when the natural} 17. Nf4 {is well met by} Nxd4 18. Nxd4 Bc6 19. Nfe2 ({
After} 19. Nfxe6 fxe6 20. Rxe6 Kh8 $19 {Black is winning. With a black rook on
f8, White does not have the idea of Rxf6.}) 19... e5 $17 {Black's advantage is
out of question.}) 16. Rad1 Bd7 17. Qe4 $6 {White allows his opponent to
achieve the optimal setup for his pieces.} ({The position was calling for} 17.
Nf4 Nxd4 18. Nxd4 {Now, the idea} Bc6 $2 {does not work in view of} 19. Nfxe6
fxe6 20. Rxe6 Kh8 21. Rxf6 $1 {There is no rook on f8!} gxf6 22. Qg6 $18) 17...
Ne7 {[%cal Gd7c6]} 18. Bd3 Ng6 19. b3 Bc6 $17 {Black has a huge advantage
since White is deprived of counterplay. Later on, Lysyj managed to win the
game.} 20. Qg4 Nf8 21. Ne5 Be8 22. Bc4 Rd6 23. Nf4 Rxd4 24. Rxd4 Qxd4 25. Nf3
Qc3 26. Nh5 Rd8 27. Kh2 Ng6 28. Rxe6 Bd7 29. Nxf6+ gxf6 30. Re8+ Kg7 0-1

