{Black's position looks slightly passive. White is planning to increase the
pressure by means of Rad1 followed by Ba2-b1. Black should look for
simplifications. The typical way of achieving this goal is} 14... Nh5 $1 {
As always, Black is ready to recapture on e7 with a knight. Afterwards, the
bishop can go to c6. In the game, White gave preference to} 15. Bg3 Nxg3 16.
hxg3 Bf6 {[%cal Gc6e7,Gd7c6] Besides putting pressure on d4, Black is planning
to proceed with ...Ne7 followed by .. .Bc6.} 17. Rad1 Ne7 18. Ne4 Bc6 $1 {
Remember this important move. After eliminating White's dark-squared bishop,
we are not afraid to double our f-pawns. In some way, this can be considered
as an improvement of the structure since Black increases his central control.
At the same time, the king will never be in danger.} 19. Nxf6+ gxf6 20. Ba2 $6
{This move is a bit too passive. When playing with an IQP, we should look for
dynamic solutions.} ({More to the point would have been} 20. d5 Bxd5 21. Bxd5
Qxd5 22. Qe3 Qf5 23. Qxa7 Rc7 $132 {when the position is dynamically balanced.}
) 20... Kg7 21. Nh2 Qa5 22. Qe2 $6 {Another passive move which allows Black to
increase his pressure on d4. Nevertheless, we should point out that Black is
slightly better anyway.} Rfd8 23. Ng4 Qh5 {Black is perfectly ready to
exchange the queens. In such a case, he will considerably increase his
advantage.} 24. Ne3 Qxe2 25. Rxe2 Bd5 {Black keeps exchanging pieces. His last
move perfectly fits into the spirit of the position.} ({Even more precise
would have been} 25... Ba4 {provoking the weakening} 26. b3 Bc6 $17 {with a
huge advantage.}) 26. Nxd5 Nxd5 27. Bb3 $6 {White is just waiting passively.} (
{In my opinion. better would have been to fix the kingside structure by means
of} 27. g4 $1) 27... Rd6 {[%cal Gc8d8,Gd5e7] Planning to increase the pressure
on d4 by means of ... Rcd8 and ...Ne7.} ({In my opinion, however, Black should
have played} 27... f5 {gaining space on the kingside and preventing g3-g4.})
28. Kf1 Ne7 29. Bc2 Rcd8 30. Red2 b6 31. Ke2 Nc6 32. Ke3 $2 {This last passive
move is probably a decisive mistake.} ({After} 32. d5 $1 exd5 33. Ba4 Ne5 34.
Rd4 {White has decent chances to make a draw.}) 32... Na5 $1 {It's important
to create another weakness. Now, White is forced to weaken the c3-square.} 33.
b3 Rc8 $19 {White is helpless against the threat of ...Rc3. Black already has
a decisive advantage.} 34. Re2 (34. Ke2 Rc3 $19) 34... Rdc6 35. Be4 Rc3+ 36.
Kf4 Nxb3 37. d5 Nd4 38. Re3 e5+ 39. Kg4 f5+ 0-1

