{[%evp 0,82,28,22,22,-6,6,6,28,42,40,21,45,49,72,49,49,48,48,33,23,23,23,0,36,
0,-18,-31,-5,-23,-28,-40,-52,-49,-25,-43,-42,-50,-38,-73,-54,-56,-56,-97,-123,
-112,-121,-121,-99,-93,-96,-95,-90,-88,-110,-88,-61,-61,-49,-64,-79,-82,-89,
-67,-44,-55,-58,-71,-39,-48,-64,-83,-76,-161,-112,-118,-127,-118,-96,-116,-100,
-113,-123,-275,-196] This game is another example of what might happen when
White is giving a passive response to the pressure on d4.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3.
Nf3 dxc4 4. e3 Nf6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. Nc3 cxd4 7. exd4 Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Bg5 h6 10.
Bh4 Nc6 11. a3 Nh5 12. Bg3 {Just like in the previous game, White prefers to
exchange his dark-squared bishop on g3.} Nxg3 13. hxg3 Bf6 14. Ne2 $2 {This
defensive move is actually a typical mistake. When our opponent has a static
advantage, we need to play as active as possible.} ({White should have played} 
14. d5 {when the following sequence is possible -} exd5 15. Nxd5 Bxb2 16. Ra2
Na5 17. Bd3 Be6 18. Rxb2 Bxd5 19. Rb5 $44 {White's compensation should be
enough for a draw.}) 14... b6 15. Rc1 Bb7 16. Qd3 Qd6 17. Rfd1 Rfd8 {The
pressure on d4 is getting stronger and stronger. Now, White can no longer play
d4-d5 under favourable circumstances.} 18. b4 Rd7 19. d5 Ne5 {This move is
enough to retain the advantage.} ({Even simpler would have been} 19... exd5 20.
Bxd5 Ne5 21. Nxe5 Qxd5 22. Qxd5 Rxd5 23. Rxd5 Bxd5 $17 {when Black's bishop
pair gives him a considerable advantage.}) 20. Nxe5 Qxe5 21. f4 (21. Nf4 exd5
22. Bxd5 Bg5 23. Bxb7 Rxd3 24. Nxd3 Qb8 25. Rc8+ Qxc8 26. Bxc8 Rxc8 $15) 21...
Qh5 22. Qf3 Qxf3 23. gxf3 exd5 $19 {Later on, Black managed to convert his
extra pawn.} 24. Bb5 Re7 25. Kf2 Bb2 26. Rb1 Bf6 27. Rbc1 Rd8 28. Nd4 Bxd4+ 29.
Rxd4 g6 30. g4 Kg7 31. Ba4 g5 32. fxg5 hxg5 33. Bb3 Rd6 34. Rcd1 Rc7 35. Ke3
Rc3+ 36. R4d3 Rxd3+ 37. Rxd3 d4+ 38. Kf2 Kf6 39. Kg3 Ba6 40. Rd1 d3 41. f4 Rd4
0-1

