{[%evp 0,105,26,16,65,48,48,50,50,12,12,18,21,4,4,26,51,-71,19,18,23,23,23,0,0,
0,0,-12,5,9,40,40,8,17,9,15,40,-6,0,0,71,-17,54,31,31,-1,23,9,107,2,19,19,43,
43,77,2,74,158,51,83,44,-119,-26,-15,-15,-26,33,-45,-52,-21,-43,-37,-29,-13,
-10,-13,-12,-22,-15,-14,-9,-16,-16,-16,-21,-54,-41,-40,-25,-44,-21,-16,-16,-21,
-16,-16,0,-29,-32,-42,-48,-41,-52,-49,-54,-52,-56,-56] When playing against an
isolated pawn, exchange operations become crucial. When it comes to
simplification, in positions with Bg5, Black should often decide whether to
play ...Nh5 or ...Nd5. This example gives some reference points. The critical
position arises after 13.Rad1.} 1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. exd5 cxd5 4. c4 Nf6 5. Nc3
Nc6 6. Bg5 dxc4 7. Bxc4 h6 8. Bh4 e6 9. Nf3 Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. a3 b6 12. Qd3
Bb7 13. Rad1 {With every move, White is increasing the pressure. He is
planning to follow with the manoeuvre Ba2-b1. Therefore, it's time to exchange
some pieces. At this point, Black played} Nh5 {We usually go for this option.
When White had played Qd3 and Rad1, however, the idea of ...Nh5 can be a bit
risky. The thing is that in many cases White can execute the advance d4-d5.} ({
More reliable is} 13... Nd5 {The only disadvantage is that Black should accept
a position with a symmetrical pawn structure.} 14. Bxd5 {The most precise
continuation.} ({After} 14. Bg3 Nxc3 15. bxc3 Bf6 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gc6a5] Black
obtains a favourable version of the semi-hanging pawns. He is ready to proceed
with ...Rc8 followed by ...Na5.}) 14... exd5 15. Bxe7 Nxe7 {[%csl Gf5][%cal
Gb7c8,Gc8g4] This kind of symmetrical position is better for White only when
he enjoys superior piece activity. Black's main problem is the light-squared
bishop. We should quickly transfer this bishop to the diagonal c8-h3.
Therefore, the next move will be ...Bc8 followed by either ...Bg4 or ... Bf5.})
14. Bg3 $1 {Now, this move is very strong. Since White is trying to execute
the advance d4-d5, he shouldn't allow Black to take the d5-square under
control after 14.Bxe7 Nxe7.} Nxg3 $6 {Black opts for the wrong move order.} ({
Better would have been} 14... Bf6 $5 {when} 15. d5 {is not that dangerous.} ({
We already know that the structure arising after} 15. Ne4 Ne7 16. Rfe1 Nxg3 17.
Nxf6+ gxf6 18. hxg3 Kg7 $11 {does not create any problems for Black.}) 15...
Na5 16. dxe6 Nxc4 17. exf7+ Rxf7 18. Qxc4 Qc8 $44 {[%cal Gf6c3,Gb7f3] Black
has an obvious compensation for the pawn. He is ready to spoil White's
structure with ...Bxc3 and ...Bxf3.}) 15. hxg3 Bf6 16. Rfe1 $6 {This slow move
gives Black enough time for ...Ne7 when Black is doing OK.} ({Critical would
have been} 16. d5 Na5 ({After} 16... exd5 17. Bxd5 Na5 18. Qb1 Bxd5 19. Nxd5
$16 {White's piece activity grants him a huge advantage.}) 17. dxe6 Nxc4 18.
exf7+ Rxf7 19. Qxc4 Qc8 20. Qb3 $16 {We have examined exactly the same
position with one small but significant difference - now the h5-knight has
been exchanged for the g3-bishop. In this case, Black cannot spoil White's
kingside structure by means of ...Bxf3. Therefore, the compensation for the
pawn is not enough.}) 16... Ne7 17. Ne5 Rc8 18. Bb3 Rc7 19. Ng4 Nf5 20. Rxe6
fxe6 21. Qxf5 Kh8 22. Qd3 e5 23. d5 e4 24. Nxe4 Bxb2 25. d6 Rd7 26. Bc2 g6 27.
Nc3 Bxa3 28. Qxg6 Qg5 29. Qe6 Rg7 30. Ne5 Bc5 31. Ng6+ Rxg6 32. Qxg6 Qxg6 33.
Bxg6 Rxf2 34. Kh2 Bxg2 35. d7 Bd5+ 36. Kh3 Be6+ 37. g4 Bxd7 38. Rxd7 Rf3+ 39.
Kg2 Rxc3 40. Rxa7 Kg8 41. Rb7 Re3 42. Kf1 Re5 43. Kg2 Re3 44. Bh5 Rc3 45. Bg6
Bd4 46. Bh5 Kh8 47. Bg6 Rb3 48. Rh7+ Kg8 49. Bf7+ Kxh7 50. Bxb3 b5 51. Kf3 Kg6
52. Ke4 Bc5 53. Kd3 1/2-1/2

