{In this example, we shall take a look at a typical manoeuvre that you should
always keep in mind when playing against IQP. In this position, Black should
decide how to develop his light-squared bishop. The most natural move would be
14...b6 with the idea of ...Bb7 on the next move. The problem, however, is
that White can play 15.Qf3. Fortunately, Black has another typical solution at
his disposal -} 14... Bd7 {[%cal Gd7c6] The idea of this thematic move is to
follow with ...Bc6 on the next move. It's very important to understand the
structure arising after} 15. Rad1 Bc6 16. Nxc6 bxc6 {Usually, this structure
is quite playable for Black if he had managed to get rid of his light-squared
bishop. With a bishop on c8, however, such a structure would be in White's
favour. In this specific case, Black has decent counterplay. The weakness of
the c6-pawn is compensated by the isolated d4-pawn and the possibility to play
along the semi-open b-file.} 17. Ne4 {White is trying to eliminate the most
important defender of the black king - the f6-knight. We know, however, that
exchanges are quite favourable for Black. The next few moves are quite logical.
} Nxe4 18. Qxe4 Qd6 19. Bd3 g6 20. h4 Rfd8 $2 {This mistake is typical for a
blitz game. Black shouldn't have allowed the advance h4-h5.} ({Of course,
Black should have played} 20... h5 $132 {with sufficient counterplay.}) 21. h5
$14 {Even though Black keeps chances of equality, White is now slightly better.
} Qxd4 22. hxg6 Nxg6 23. Qxd4 Rxd4 24. Bxg6 Rxd1 25. Bxf7+ Kxf7 26. Rxd1 Ke7
27. Rd4 Rb8 28. b3 Rb5 29. f3 Rd5 30. Ra4 a5 31. Kf2 h5 32. Kg3 Rg5+ 33. Kh3
Rd5 34. g3 Kf6 35. Rc4 Rd2 36. Ra4 Rd5 37. f4 Kg6 38. Rc4 Rd2 39. Rxc6 Kf6 40.
a4 Rd3 41. Rc5 Rxb3 42. Rxh5 1-0

