{In the next three examples, we shall take a look at White's most ambitious
attacking setup - the battery Bc2 and Qd3. In this case, Black should decide
how to fight against the pressure on h7.} 1. d4 e6 2. e4 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6 4. Bd3
c5 5. c3 cxd4 6. cxd4 dxe4 7. Nxe4 Bb4+ 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. Nf3 O-O 10. O-O b6 11. a3
Be7 12. Re1 Bb7 13. Bc2 {[%cal Gd1d3] In my opinion, this is the most
dangerous continuation. White is ready to play Qd3 on the next move.} Rc8 14.
Qd3 g6 $1 {This move should be played immediately since White is threatening
d4-d5.} ({White's tactical idea can be seen in the line} 14... a6 $2 15. d5 $1
exd5 16. Bg5 {[%cal Gg5f6]} g6 ({The alternative} 16... Ne4 {does not help
either. For example, after} 17. Nxe4 dxe4 18. Qxe4 g6 19. Qh4 $18 {White has a
winning initiative.}) 17. Rxe7 Qxe7 18. Nxd5 $18 {Black can already resign.})
15. Bh6 Re8 16. Rad1 {White has already mobilized all his forces. After
provoking the advance ...g7-g6, he will transfer the bishop to the diagonal
a2-g8. Afterwards, the idea will be to execute the break d4-d5 under
favourable circumstances. Black's best defensive strategy is to transfer the
dark-squared bishop to g7.} Bf8 17. Bg5 h6 $1 {Another important inclusion.
Before playing ...Bg7, we should force the move Bh4.} ({The immediate} 17...
Bg7 $6 {is well met by} 18. h4 h6 19. h5 $40 {when White's attack is getting
very dangerous.}) 18. Bh4 Bg7 {Black managed to stabilize the position. He can
already consider the manoeuvre...Ne7-f5. Therefore, White should play
energetically. The most ambitious try is} 19. Ba4 {introducing the idea of Ne5.
} ({After the passive} 19. Bb3 {Black can play} Ne7 {[%cal Ge7f5] followed by .
..Nf5. I would prefer playing this position with Black.}) 19... Qd6 20. Ne5 ({
Another interesting option is} 20. Bb3 {when Black should play} Qf8 $1 {
[%cal Gc6e7,Ge7f5] Black is preparing the maneuver ...Ne7-f5.} ({The immediate
} 20... Ne7 $2 {runs into} 21. Nb5 $16 {[%csl Ra7] when Black loses the
a7-pawn.}) 21. Ne5 Nxe5 22. dxe5 Nh5 23. f3 Nf4 24. Qd7 Rb8 $132 {Black has
enough counterplay. The e5-pawn is already a source of problems for White. One
of the possible ideas is ...g6-g5 followed by ...Ng6. 1/2-1/2 (49) Gonzalez,J 
(2147)-Martins Barriga,F (2210) ICCF email 2007 Corr 2013 [Bc2+Qd3]}) 20...
Red8 {Black escaped for the pin. White's try for an advantage is connected
with the sacrifice of the d4-pawn. He should play} 21. Qh3 Nxd4 22. Bb3 $1 {
Obviously, such a precise play can be seen only in correspondence chess. White
is planning to take on f7. It turns out, however, that Black has nothing to
worry about. The following sequence is pretty much forced.} Qc7 23. Nxf7 Qxf7
24. Rxd4 Nd5 25. Rdd1 Nf4 26. Rxd8+ Rxd8 27. Qg4 Rd2 28. Rxe6 Kh8 29. Re7 Qxb3
{At this point, the draw was agreed. A logical follow-up would have been} 30.
h3 Rxb2 31. Qxf4 Qxc3 32. Rxb7 ({Let me provide another funny line -} 32. Qb8+
Bc8 33. Bg3 Rc2 34. Kh2 Qc5 35. Qxa7 Rxf2 36. Bxf2 Qxf2 37. Qc7 Qf8 38. Rxg7
Qxg7 39. Qxc8+ Kh7 $11 {Once again, with equality.}) 32... Qe1+ 33. Kh2 Qe5 $11
{with equality.} 1/2-1/2

