{[%evp 0,34,19,9,18,-10,32,23,32,44,41,53,45,45,55,62,75,49,54,35,24,25,47,45,
62,44,36,72,72,53,53,53,39,30,26,26,31] At the end of the lecture, I would
like to provide an important theoretical information. After studying the games,
you can be tempted to use the following move order} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3
Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O cxd4 7. exd4 Be7 8. Nc3 O-O {The immediate
recapture on d4 makes your repertoire very simple. You get rid of all systems
based on dxc5. Of course, everything comes at a price. Now, for example, White
has a wide choice of attacking setups. So far, we have covered two attacking
constructions: 1) Setups based on Bg5 2) Battery Bc2+Qd3 In this last example,
I would like to give some directions regarding another very interesting option
-} 9. Qe2 {White is planning to proceed with Rd1 and only then decide how to
deploy the other minor pieces. In my opinion, Black should play} a6 {[%cal
Gb7b5,Gc8b7] planning to follow with ...b7-b5 and ...Bb7.} 10. Rd1 ({Usually,
when the black knight is still on b8, the move} 10. a4 {is not a good idea in
view of} Nc6 11. Rd1 Nb4 {This is the point. The b4-square is the perfect spot
for the black knight.} 12. Ne5 Bd7 $1 {We are already familiar with this
thematic idea. Black will follow with ...Bc6.} 13. Bg5 Bc6 $132 {We know that
the structure arising after} 14. Nxc6 bxc6 {is quite playable for Black since
he managed to get rid of his light-squared bishop.}) 10... b5 11. Bb3 {This is
the most ambitious choice. White keeps control of the important d5-square,
thus supporting the advance d4-d5.} ({After} 11. Bd3 Bb7 12. Bg5 Nbd7 13. Rac1
Rc8 14. Ne5 Nd5 $11 {Black manages to comfortably equalize.}) 11... Bb7 12. Bg5
{Sooner or later, White must go for this move.} ({After} 12. Ne5 {Black has
the additional option of} Nc6 ({The alternative} 12... Nbd7 13. Bg5 Rc8 {
transposes to the main line.}) 13. Be3 Na5 14. Bc2 Rc8 $15 {Black is already
slightly better.}) 12... Nbd7 13. d5 {As always, this advance does not work
very well when Black managed to mobilize his forces.} ({Another attacking idea
is} 13. Ne5 Rc8 14. Rd3 {This rook lift is quite typical for IQP type of
positions.} ({Once again, the advance} 14. d5 {does not create problems for
Black. The simplifications arising after} exd5 15. Nxd7 Qxd7 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17.
Nxd5 Bxd5 18. Rxd5 Qe8 $11 {lead to equality.}) 14... b4 $1 {This move is an
important part of Black's strategy. The knight should go far away from the
centre.} 15. Na4 Nxe5 16. dxe5 Nd5 17. Bxe7 Qxe7 $132 {Black has sufficient
counterplay.}) 13... exd5 14. Nxd5 {This move leads to simplifications and
full equality.} Bxd5 15. Bxd5 Nxd5 16. Rxd5 Bxg5 17. Nxg5 h6 18. Rad1 ({
The alternative} 18. Qd2 hxg5 19. Rxd7 Qf6 $11 {leads to equality as well.})
18... Re8 19. Qd2 hxg5 20. Rxd7 Qf6 $11 {with equality.} *

