{With this game we will start the examination of the line 1.d4 d5 2.c4 dxc4 3.
e3} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e3 {As I already discussed in the previous example,
White is trying to avoid some nasty systems after 3.Nf3, but the drawback is
that Black can continue with 3...e5} e5 4. Bxc4 Nc6 $5 {I quite like this move,
because it leads to an interesting dynamic position with good chances for
Black to take the initiative.} 5. d5 $6 {This move is not very ambitious, in
my opinion} Nce7 (5... Na5 {is the clear equalizer} 6. Qa4+ c6 7. dxc6 Nxc6 {
but the text move looks more ambitious.}) 6. Nf3 (6. e4 {In the other game
White continues with the straightforward 6.e4} Ng6 {Black's effortless setup.
He plays Ng6,Bd6, a6 and then starts some actions on the kingside, usually by
f7-f5 break or by means of the piece attack.} 7. Ne2 Bd6 8. Nbc3 a6 9. a4 {
This is just a waste of time, Black is not planning to play b7-b5. Usually the
b-pawn should stay on b7} Nf6 10. h3 O-O 11. Be3 Qe7 12. Qd2 Bc5 {Black
exchanges the defender of the dark squares.} 13. a5 Bxe3 14. Qxe3 Ne8 {now the
knight will land on "d6" and then the idea is f7-f5.} 15. O-O Nd6 16. Ba2 f5
17. f3 f4 {without the dark-squared bishop this advance is powerful. Now Black
is playing in the KID manner and White's position will collapse soon.} 18. Qc5
Nh4 19. Kh2 Rf6 20. Rac1 Nxg2 {Nice tactical shot which ends the game.} 21.
Kxg2 Rg6+ 22. Kh1 Bxh3 23. Rf2 Qh4 24. Rh2 Bg2+ 25. Kg1 Bxf3+ {0-1 (25) Hamley,
R (2089)-Alekseenko,K (2696) Chess.com INT 2020}) 6... Ng6 7. Bb5+ (7. h4 Bd6
8. h5 Nf8 {[%cal Rh7h6,Rf8d7,Rg8f6] with a double-edged position.}) 7... Bd7 8.
Qb3 Rb8 {I like this move. In this structure, you should avoid moving the
b-pawn, because this will create a lot of weaknesses on the queenside.} 9. O-O
Nf6 10. Nc3 Bd6 {Black builds his optimal setup, later he will try to open the
kingside by means of f5} 11. Bxd7+ Qxd7 12. e4 O-O 13. Be3 b5 (13... a6 {
I would prefer this small move, but Aronian was more ambitious}) 14. Bxa7 Ra8 (
14... b4 15. Bxb8 bxc3 {with an excellent compensation for the exchange}) 15.
Nxb5 Nf4 16. a4 (16. Nd2 $1 {this move would give White an advantage. It is
not so clear how Black will develop any initiative.}) 16... Qg4 17. g3 (17. Ne1
{was more stubborn according to the engine}) 17... Nxe4 18. Rfe1 {White
collapsed just for a few moves.} (18. Kh1 $1) 18... Nh3+ 19. Kf1 Rxa7 $4 (19...
f5 $1 $19) 20. Nxa7 $4 {White missed his chance to level the game.} (20. Rxe4
Qxe4 21. Nxa7 $11) 20... Nhxf2 21. Nb5 f5 22. Nxd6 cxd6 23. Re2 f4 24. Rxf2
fxg3 25. hxg3 Qxg3 26. Rg2 Rxf3+ {This was just a blitz game and both sides
made mistakes, but I like the concept of Black's play.} 0-1

