1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e3 e5 4. Bxc4 Nc6 5. Nf3 e4 {I should warn you that the
engines almost always prefer White in this line. This is a good thing in my
opinion, because over the board I never had this feeling. Black's position is
relatively easy to play and even if objectively Black is not equalizing, in
practice, White experienced severe problems in this line.} 6. Qb3 (6. Nfd2 {
Is the main alternative which we will see in the next game.}) 6... Nh6 (6...
Bb4+) 7. Nfd2 f5 {The most straightforward continuation} (7... Qg5 8. Nxe4 Qxg2
9. Ng3) 8. Nc3 Bd6 9. Be2 {The most consistent move. White is preparing the
advance f2-f3 and freeing the c4-square for the knight.} (9. a3 {was tried by
Mamedyarov, but I don't think it is hazardous} a6 (9... Qd7 10. Qa4 a6 (10...
Nd8 11. Qxd7+ $14) 11. Ba2 $14 {1-0 (41) Mamedyarov,S (2767)-Alekseenko, K  
(2702) Warsaw 2021}) 10. h3 (10. Bd5 Qg5 11. g3 Ne7) 10... Qh4) 9... Nf7 10.
Nc4 Be7 11. O-O O-O {Three games reached this position. Black scores two draws
and one win. Nevertheless, this position is critical for the evaluation of the
6.Qb3 line} 12. d5 $5 $146 {New.} (12. Rd1 {Looks more logical and was played
twice, but I believe Aronian wanted to keep the rook on f1 in order to push
f2-f3} Kh8 {Black should unpin the knight} 13. Bd2 (13. a3 {seems too slow} a6
14. Qc2 b5 $1 (14... Nd6 $6 15. Ne5 $14 {1/2-1/2 (68) Leenhouts,K (2478)
-Alekseenko,K (2590) Stockholm 2017}) 15. Ne5 Bb7 $11 {Black completes the
development and can be optimistic for the future}) 13... a6 14. Rac1 $2 (14. a4
$5 {could be a possible improvement to stop b7-b5 break} Nd6 (14... a5 {
[%cal Rc6b4] Is very interesting to take control of the b4-square} 15. Be1 $1 {
I failed to find equality after this move.} (15. Nb5 Be6 $11 {[%cal Re6d5]})
15... Bb4 16. Rac1 Rb8 {[%cal Rc8d7]} (16... Bd7 17. Nd5 $14) 17. d5 Nce5 18.
Nb5 Bxe1 19. Rxe1 Ng6 {[%cal Rf5f4]} 20. Nxa5 {Black has some compensation for
the pawn, but I am not sure if it is enough. Against the engine, Black is
worse, but during the practical game I will not underestimate Black's chances
on the kingside.}) 15. Ne5 Rf6 {[%cal Rc8e6,Re7f8,Rf6h6]}) (14. Be1 $5 {
Looks logical, but runs to} b5 15. Ne5 Ncxe5 16. dxe5 Qe8 $11) 14... b5 $1 15.
Ne5 Ncxe5 16. dxe5 c6 {and Black is much better due to the weak e5-pawn
Kovalenko,I (2624)-Kanep,M (2440) Liepaja 2018, but ½-½ (38).}) 12... Nb8 13.
f3 $2 {The dark squares will be very weak now.} (13. Rd1 Kh8 14. Bd2 {[%cal
Rb8d7,Ra7a6,Rd7c5]}) 13... exf3 14. Bxf3 Nd7 15. e4 Nd6 (15... Nc5 {I am not
sure, what Shakh didn't like about} 16. Qc2 Nd6 17. Nxd6 Bxd6 {Black has a
very nice position}) 16. Be3 Nxc4 17. Qxc4 Ne5 18. Qb3 Bd6 19. Nb5 Qh4 20. Nxd6
cxd6 21. g3 $6 (21. Be2 f4 22. Bd4 Qg5 $11) 21... Qe7 $15 {and Black converts
his advantage.} 22. Bg2 fxe4 23. Rxf8+ Qxf8 24. Rc1 Nf3+ 25. Kh1 Qf7 26. Bf4
Qh5 27. h4 g5 $1 28. Bxd6 gxh4 29. Bxf3 exf3 30. gxh4 Qxh4+ 31. Bh2 Qe4 $1 32.
Qc2 $2 Qxd5 33. Rg1+ Kf8 34. Bd6+ $2 Ke8 35. Re1+ Be6 36. Qa4+ b5 37. Rxe6+
Qxe6 38. Qxb5+ Kf7 39. Qh5+ Kg8 40. Qg5+ Kf7 41. Qh5+ Kg7 42. Be5+ Kg8 43. Qxf3
Rd8 44. Qg3+ Qg6 45. Qb3+ Kf8 46. Qb4+ Ke8 47. Qb5+ Rd7 48. Qb8+ Ke7 49. Qb4+
Ke6 50. Qe1 Qf5 51. Bc3+ Kf7 52. Qe2 Rd3 53. Qg2 Qh3+ 54. Qxh3 Rxh3+ 55. Kg2
Rxc3 0-1

