1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e3 e5 4. Bxc4 Nc6 $5 5. Nf3 e4 (5... exd4 6. O-O $1) 6.
Nfd2 Qg5 7. Nxe4 (7. g3 {Is the alternative, but Black has an effortless play
after :} Nf6 8. Nc3 Bb4 9. a3 Bxc3 10. bxc3 O-O 11. Bb2 Bg4 12. Be2 Qf5 {
0-1 (39) Dubov,D (2677)-Alekseenko,K (2563) Sochi 2017}) 7... Qxg2 8. Ng3 Qh3
$1 {The queen heads for a safe and active square on h4.} 9. Nc3 Bd6 ({Probably
more accurate is and we should play this} 9... Nf6 $1 10. e4 (10. Bd2 Bd6 11.
Bf1 Qh4 12. Bg2 Bh3 $11) 10... Bg4 11. f3 $4 (11. Qa4 $1 Bd7 12. Be3 Ne5 13.
Qb3 Nf3+ 14. Kd1 O-O-O {With a very sharp play}) 11... O-O-O $1 {Riazantsev,A 
(2649)-Moiseenko,V (2501) St Petersburg 2018, 1-0 (142),} 12. fxg4 (12. Bf1 Qh4
13. fxg4 Nxd4) 12... Nxd4 13. Bf1 Qh4 14. Be3 Bc5 {With more than enough
compensation for the sacrificing material}) 10. Qf3 (10. Nce4 Bxg3 11. Nxg3 Nf6
$11 {[%cal Re8g8]}) (10. Qh5 {The endgame could be tiny better for White} Qxh5
11. Nxh5 g6 12. Ng3 f5) 10... Nh6 $2 {I don't like this move} ({The natural :} 
10... Nf6 11. Bf1 Bg4 $5 {Gives Black enough counterplay}) 11. Bf1 (11. Qe4+ {
could be annoying}) 11... Qh4 12. Qe4+ Qxe4 13. Ngxe4 Be7 14. Nd5 O-O $6 (14...
Bd8 $1 {Black should keep the bishop pair.}) 15. Bg2 Bd8 {The endgame is level,
probably with a slight advantage for White. Andreiking manages to win at the
end.} 16. Bd2 Nf5 17. Rg1 Nce7 18. Nxe7+ Bxe7 19. d5 a5 20. O-O-O Nh4 21. Bh1
Ra6 22. Bc3 Ng6 23. Bf3 f5 24. Ng5 Bf6 25. d6 Bxc3 26. bxc3 cxd6 27. Bd5+ Kh8
28. Nf7+ Rxf7 29. Bxf7 Ne5 30. Bd5 a4 31. Rd4 g6 32. Rgd1 Ra5 33. f4 Ng4 34.
Rc4 Bd7 35. Rc7 Nxe3 36. Re1 Nxd5 37. Rxd7 Ra8 38. Rxb7 Rc8 39. Kb2 Nxf4 40.
Ree7 Nd3+ 41. Kc2 Ne5 42. Rxh7+ Kg8 43. Rbg7+ Kf8 44. Ra7 Kg8 45. Rhc7 Re8 46.
Rxa4 g5 47. Raa7 f4 48. Rg7+ Kf8 49. Rh7 Kg8 50. Rag7+ Kf8 51. Rxg5 Re6 52.
Rf5+ Kg8 53. Rh3 Ng6 54. a4 Kg7 55. a5 Re1 56. Rd3 Ne5 57. Rxd6 f3 58. a6 1-0

