{For this lecture, I investigated the move 6...Nc6 and I find it a pretty good
option and a good replacement of the more popular 6...a6. It was tried with
big success by the American GMs Dominguez and Xiong. With this move, you want
to minimize White's options on move 7. Also Black is developing a pretty
useful piece. The only drawback is that Black is not that flexible and can't
go to d7-square.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e3 Nf6 4. Bxc4 e6 5. Nf3 c5 6. O-O Nc6
7. Nc3 (7. a3 a6 (7... cxd4) 8. dxc5 {I believe in this move order, the
endgame is not that dangerous for Black} Qxd1 9. Rxd1 Bxc5 10. b4 Be7 {This is
the right square for the bishop. Black can challenge the queenside later by
means of a6-a5.} 11. Bb2 O-O 12. Nbd2 Rd8 13. Be2 Bd7 14. Nb3 Be8 15. Rdc1 (15.
Nfd2 {Prag tried this line himself with White and lost the game after:} Rac8
16. Bf3 Nd5 17. Rac1 Nb6 {[%cal Rb6a4] The knight will come to a4 soon and
Black will be excellent.} 18. Nc5 Bxc5 $5 19. bxc5 Na4 20. Ba1 Na5 21. Bd4 Bc6
22. Be2 Bd5 23. f4 Rd7 24. Kf2 Rdc7 25. e4 Bb3 26. Nxb3 Nxb3 {Black won a pawn
and later the game. 0-1 (53) Praggnanandhaa,R (2608) -Dominguez Perez,L (2758)
chess24.com INT 2021}) 15... Ne4 16. Rc4 {This is a typical idea, Black is
transferring the knight to the d6-square.} Nd6 17. Rc2 a5 18. bxa5 {Black is
the only one who can play for an advantage after this break.} Nxa5 19. Nxa5
Rxa5 20. Rc7 Bf6 21. Bxf6 gxf6 22. h3 Rda8 23. Rd1 Nb5 {Black decides to force
a draw.} 24. Bxb5 Bxb5 25. Rxb7 Bc6 26. Rc7 Bxf3 27. gxf3 Rxa3 28. Rdd7 Rf8 29.
f4 f5 30. Re7 Ra6 31. Kg2 Kg7 32. Kg3 Kf6 33. Ra7 {½-½ (33) Vidit,S (2727)
-Praggnanandhaa,R (2610) Kolkata 2021}) 7... a6 8. Ne5 {I don't find this move
dangerous and this game proves it.} (8. a4 {I don't like this move, especially
when Black's knight is already on c6. It usually transposes to 6.a4 variation.}
Be7 (8... Qc7 {avoiding queens exchange also looks good.}) 9. dxc5 (9. Qe2 {
Is well met by:} O-O 10. Rd1 Qc7 11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. Bd2 b6 13. Rac1 Bb7 14. Be1
$6 Ne5 $1 {And Black gets the initiative 0-1 (31) Krallis,C (2409)-Deac,B  
(2651) Chess.com INT 2021}) 9... Qxd1 10. Rxd1 Bxc5 {The endgame is harmless
for Black with White's pawn already on a4. White can't advance a3-b4 as usual
and also Black has a nice b4-square for his minor pieces.} 11. Bd3 O-O {
0-1 (58) Ivanchuk,V (2678)-Xiong,J (2686) Chess.com INT 2021}) 8... Qc7 ({
The straightforward:} 8... Nxe5 {is also possible} 9. dxe5 Qxd1 10. Rxd1 Nd7
11. f4 (11. Be2 {The pawn sacrifice also didn't promise an advantage} Nxe5 12.
b3 Bd7 {White probably has enough compensation, but definitely not more than
that.}) 11... b5) 9. Nxc6 Qxc6 10. d5 (10. Be2 $5 Bd6 11. dxc5 Qxc5 12. Bd2 {
and White can ask some questions}) 10... exd5 (10... Qc7 11. dxe6 Bxe6 12. Bxe6
fxe6 {looks ugly for Black, but it seems that it is playable.}) 11. Nxd5 b5 12.
Nxf6+ Qxf6 13. Bd5 Rb8 14. e4 (14. Bd2 b4 15. e4 Be7 16. b3 $14) 14... Be7 15.
a4 O-O 16. axb5 Rxb5 $5 17. Ra3 Rb6 $6 (17... Bd6 $11) 18. Rf3 Qe5 19. Bd2 $1
Rg6 20. Bc3 Qc7 21. Rg3 Bb7 22. Rxg6 hxg6 23. Bxb7 Qxb7 24. Qg4 $6 (24. Qa4 $14
) 24... c4 $1 25. e5 Bb4 $1 {The crucial justification.} 26. Bxb4 Qxb4 27. e6
Qxb2 28. Qxc4 Qf6 29. Qxa6 Qxe6 30. Qxe6 fxe6 31. Kh1 Kh8 32. Kg1 Kg8 33. Kh1
Kh8 34. Kg1 Kg8 1/2-1/2

