1. Nf3 d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 dxc4 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O Nc6 7. Nc3 a6 8. d5 {
This is the most critical line in my opinion} Nxd5 {I like very much this new
idea} ({Both} 8... Na5) ({and} 8... exd5 {didn't bring full equality}) 9. Nxd5
Na5 10. b3 {Giri and Tari chose this move, but I think it is quite harmless
and Black has a very good position after it.} (10. e4 $146 {This move is never
played, but I expect some games here shortly, because it is the top choice of
the engine and the only critical continuation. This move definetely looks
dangerous for an unprepared opponent, but we have nothing to worry about.
Black should take the bishop and neutralize White's initiative with few
accurate moves. Later, Black's bishop pair will give him enough counterplay
not only to equalize but very often to take the initiative.} Nxc4 11. Bg5 Qd7
12. b3 {looks logical, but didn't bring much after:} (12. Qe2 {Is very sharp}
b5 13. b3 (13. Rfe1 {Another interesting continuation} Bd6 14. b3 O-O 15. Nf6+
gxf6 16. Bxf6 e5 17. bxc4 Qe6 {and Black is pretty much safe}) (13. Rad1 exd5
14. exd5+ Be7 15. Rfe1 f6 16. d6 Nxd6 17. Ne5 {a fantastic play, but Black
just gets too much material} fxe5 18. Qxe5 Qe6 19. Qf4 Bxg5 20. Rxe6+ Bxe6 {
White can't take all, so Black will have enough time to consolidate the
position and get at least equal chances} 21. Qxg5 (21. Qe5 Nf5 22. Qxe6+ Ne7
$11 {[%cal Rg5f6]} 23. g3 Bf6 24. h4 h5 {[%cal Rh8h6,Re8f8]}) 21... Nf5 $11 {
[%cal Re8g8,Re8f7]}) 13... exd5 14. exd5+ Be7 15. bxc4 (15. Rfe1 f6 16. bxc4
Kf7 $11 {[%cal Rh8e8] Black's king is very safe on f7. I analyze a bit more to
illustrate the ideas for both sides.} 17. a4 (17. Qe4) 17... b4 18. Qe4 Bd6 19.
Bf4 Qc7 20. Bxd6 Qxd6 21. Nd2 Bd7 22. Qe3 Rhe8 23. Ne4 Qc7 24. Qxc5 Qxc5 25.
Nxc5 Bf5 {[%cal Ra8c8]} 26. Nb3 $4 Bc2) 15... f6 16. Bf4 O-O 17. a4 b4 18. Nd2
Rd8) 12... exd5 13. exd5 f6 14. bxc4 (14. Re1+ {Transposes} Kf7 15. bxc4 Bd6)
14... Bd6 $1 15. Bh4 O-O (15... b5 {is also very good, because Black's king is
quite comfortable on f7} 16. Re1+ Kf7 17. Qc2 Qf5 {[%cal Rc8b7] I clicked this
position a bit and it seems quite good for Black. The bishop pair gives Black
enough counterplay. Even If White manages to exchange the dark-squared bishop,
then the d5-weakness will be important}) 16. a4 f5 17. Re1 h6 18. a5 Qf7 {
With the threat g7-g5 in the air, Black should be quite optimistic. The engine
gives some strange line, but I can't see a single problem for Black here.})
10... Nxc4 11. bxc4 exd5 12. cxd5 Bd6 13. e4 f6 $1 {What we get here, a
somehow ugly looking position for Black, but the potential of the bishop pair
shouldn't be underestimated. White's central pawns are well blocked and Black
has 3 against 1 on the queenside.} 14. a4 O-O 15. h3 {White is trying to
restrict the light-squared bishop} (15. a5 Bg4 $1 {the pin is quite annoying
and only Black can be better here.} (15... b5 $6 16. axb6 Qxb6 17. Qc2 {
1-0 (67) Giri,A (2764)-Wang,H (2763) Chess.com INT 2020})) 15... b6 {not
allowing a4-a5 and preparing slowly the advance of the queenside pawns.} 16.
Bb2 Bd7 17. Re1 Qc7 18. e5 fxe5 19. Nxe5 Rae8 20. Qb3 (20. Nc4 $5) 20... b5 $1
{Finally Black manages to advance his queenside pawns and he has an advantage.}
21. axb5 axb5 22. Nxd7 Rxe1+ 23. Rxe1 Qxd7 $17 24. Re6 c4 (24... Rf5 $1) 25.
Qe3 b4 26. Be5 Bxe5 27. Qxe5 Qf7 28. Qd4 b3 29. Qxc4 b2 30. Qb4 Qxf2+ 31. Kh2
h5 32. Rb6 h4 33. Qd6 $4 (33. Qxb2 $1 Qg3+ 34. Kg1 Qe1+ $11) 33... Re8 34. Rb4
Re2 35. Qd8+ Qf8 36. Qb6 Qf6 37. Qb8+ Kh7 38. Rg4 Re1 39. Rb4 Qf2 0-1

