1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 a6 6. a4 c5 7. O-O Nc6 8. Qe2
Qc7 $5 {I like the idea of maintaining the central tension. This will make it
particularly hard for White to find a good square for the c1-bishop while
retaining the possibility of giving White an IQP under more favourable
circumstances later. White usually reacts to this by preparing the d4-d5
advance or by taking on c5 and placing the bishop on b2} (8... Be7 $6 {allows
White a typical expansion in the centre that will culminate with a strong
kingside initiative after} 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. e4 Ng4 (10... e5 $2 11. Bxf7+ $1
Kxf7 12. Qc4+ $16) 11. e5 Nd4 12. Nxd4 Qxd4 13. Na3 $1 Bxa3 14. Rxa3 Nxe5 15.
b3 $40) (8... cxd4 $6 {I think this capture is quite premature. Black has many
useful moves he can make first, which is not as true of White's position. As
we'll see, one of Black's main strategies is to enter IQP position only when
it is a clearly improved version for him} 9. Rd1 Be7 10. exd4 O-O 11. Nc3 {
leads to a classical IQP position, where White gets a powerful initiative in
compensation for his damaged queenside.} Nd5 (11... Nb4 12. Bg5 $14 (12. Ne5 $5
)) 12. Qe4 $14 (12. Bd3 $5) (12. Bb3 $5)) 9. Nc3 {This is White's most
straight/forward plan. He intends to prepare the d5 pawn break. Now Black must
ask himself, once white plays d4-d5, where will his dark-squared bishop be
better off: d6 or e7?} ({Now we see that Black gainst a critical tempo if
White decides to play} 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. e4 $6 (10. Rd1 {transposes to 9.Rd1})
10... Ng4 11. g3 (11. h3 $4 Nd4 $1 $19 {a thematic trap}) 11... O-O (11... h5
$5 $36) 12. Bf4 e5 13. Bd2 Be6 14. Na3 Qe7) 9... Be7 {the bishop is seemingly
more passive here, but it allows Black to take the critically important
d5-square under control by means of ...0-0 and ...Rd8} 10. Rd1 (10. dxc5 Bxc5
11. b3 (11. e4 Ng4 $1 {is Black's thematic response} 12. g3 (12. h3 $4 Nd4 13.
Nxd4 Qh2#) 12... Bd6 13. h3 Nge5 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. f4 Bd4+ 16. Be3 O-O 17. Rfd1
Bxe3+ 18. Qxe3 b6 $11) (11. Rd1 O-O {transposes to the main line}) ({White can
try to make immediate use of the c-file with} 11. Bd2 O-O 12. Rfc1 (12. Rfd1 {
the d-file does not seem to be as important as the c-file. It's not surprising
that Black is able to finish his development comfortably} Bd7 13. Bd3 Be7 14.
Ne4 Nd5 15. Be1 Rfd8 16. Rac1 Be8 17. Nc3 Ndb4 18. Bb1 Rxd1 19. Rxd1 Rd8 $11 {
0-1 (81) Faizrakhmanov,R (2419)-Lysyj,I (2630) Sochi 2018}) 12... Rd8 13. Bd3
Ne5 (13... Bb4 $5 14. Ne4 Nd5 $11) 14. Be4 Nxf3+ 15. Bxf3 Qe7 (15... Qe5 16. g3
Bb4 17. Rd1 Rb8 18. e4 $14 {aside from the pressure along the c-file Black has
to deal with his lagging queenside development. This is exactly the kind of
position white would like to achieve (and Black should avoid) as was
illustrated in the game Leitao, R (2632)-Molina, R (2416) Rio de Janeiro 2013})
16. Ne4 Nxe4 17. Bxe4 Rb8 18. Bc3 Bd6 (18... b6 $2 19. Bxh7+ Kxh7 20. Qh5+ Kg8
21. Qe5 $18) 19. Qf3 b6 20. Rd1 a5 21. Rd2 Ba6 22. Rad1 Bb4 $11) (11. h3 O-O
12. Rd1 {transposes to the main line}) 11... O-O 12. Bb2 Qe7 $1 ({Black should
always be on the lookout for the possibility that White might launch a
kingside attack based on the move Ng5. For example, after} 12... b6 $6 13. Ng5
Bb7 14. Nce4 Nxe4 15. Nxe4 Bb4 16. Nf6+ $1 Kh8 (16... gxf6 17. Qg4+ Kh8 18.
Bxf6#) 17. Qh5 h6 18. Nd5 exd5 19. Qxh6+ Kg8 20. Qxg7#) 13. Ng5 Bd7 (13... b6
$6 14. Nce4 Nxe4 15. Nxe4 Bb4 16. Qf3 Bb7 17. Nf6+ $1 Kh8 (17... gxf6 18. Bxf6
$18 {[%cal Rf3g3]}) 18. Qe4 $18) 14. Nce4 Nxe4 15. Nxe4 Bb4 16. Qf3 {[%cal
Re4f6]} f5 $1 (16... f6 $5) 17. Ng3 Na5 $132) (10. b3 O-O 11. Bb2 cxd4 $1 {
this is Black's standard response when white has maintained the tension for
too long} (11... b6 12. d5 exd5 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Bxd5 $14) 12. exd4 Rd8 13.
Rac1 Na5 {if we compare this IQP to the one that arises in the main line, we
see that the black queen will not feel as comfortable on d6. For example, after
} (13... Qd6 $6 14. Rfd1 Nb4 15. Ne5 Bd7 16. Ba3 $36 {[%csl Rd6]}) 14. Rfd1 Bd7
15. Ne5 Be8 $13) (10. d5 {looks premature, especially since black has not yet
played ...b6} exd5 11. Nxd5 Nxd5 12. Bxd5 O-O 13. Bd2 Bf6 14. Bc3 Bxc3 15. bxc3
Ne7 16. Bc4 Bd7 $11 {Black has a comfortable game}) 10... O-O {Thus we arrive
at the critical position of the 9.Nc3 variation. Black will continue with his
plan and if White keeps the tension for too long then we will likely enter a
favourable IQP middlegame} 11. Bd2 {a useful waiting move, reserving the
d5-push for when black plays ...b6} (11. h3 Rd8 12. d5 {this pawn break loses
a lot of strength if the black pawn is still on b7} (12. b3 cxd4 {I like this
approach in general. Once Black has brought the rook to d8 and White decides
to maintain the tension, then Black is usually ready to enter the IQP positions
} (12... b6 $6 {Black should always be sceptical of this move} 13. Bb2 Bb7 14.
d5 exd5 15. Nxd5 Nxd5 16. Bxd5 Na5 17. Be5 Qc8 18. e4 Bxd5 19. exd5 Nxb3 20.
Rab1 $16) (12... Nb4 $5 13. Bb2 Bd7 14. dxc5 Bxc5 15. Ng5 Bd6 16. Rac1 Bc6 $11
{0-1 (38) Bonin,J (2385)-Dlugy,M (2525) New York 1990}) 13. exd4 Na5 14. Bg5 h6
15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Ne4 Be7 17. Rac1 Nxc4 18. Rxc4 Qb6 19. Qe3 Bd7 20. Ne5 Be8
$13 {0-1 (20) Lerner,K (2523) -Ivanchuk,V (2734) Odessa/Istanbul 2006}) ({
The symmetrical pawn structure arising after} 12. dxc5 Rxd1+ 13. Qxd1 Bxc5 {
is not problematic for Black since White has already weakened his queenside
with the advance a2-a4.} 14. b3 b6 (14... Bd7 $5) 15. Bb2 Bb7 16. Qe2 Na5 $15 {
Black is already slightly better. White is forced to give his c4-bishop.})
12... exd5 13. Bxd5 (13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Bxd5 Nb4 15. e4 (15. Bc4 Rxd1+ 16. Qxd1
Bf5 17. Qe2 Bf6 $15) 15... Nxd5 16. exd5 Bf5 $11 {0-1 (37) Oblitas Guerrero,C 
(2480)-Granda Zuniga,J (2620) Lima 1994}) 13... Nb4 $1 {here we see why
keeping the pawn on b7 makes a difference, the knight is not pinned!} 14. e4
Nfxd5 15. exd5 Bf5 16. Qc4 Bd6 $15 {0-1 (30) Garcia, M (2144)-Granda Zuniga, J
(2641) Navalmoral 2012 Black enjoys a bishop pair and powerful piece play.}) (
11. b3 Rd8 12. Bb2 cxd4 {this leads to yet another version of the type of IQP
middlegames we're willing to enter} (12... b6 13. d5 $14) 13. exd4 Na5 14. Rac1
Bd7 15. d5 Nxc4 16. bxc4 Rac8 17. Nd4 e5 $17) (11. d5 {again we see this break
crash and burn when the black pawn is still on b7} exd5 12. Nxd5 (12. Bxd5 Nb4
$1 $132) 12... Nxd5 13. Bxd5 Nb4 14. Bc4 Bf6 15. e4 Bg4 $11 {0-1 (29) Schmidt,
P (2412)-Sadler,M (2668) Germany 1999}) (11. dxc5 {if White is intending on
capturing on c5, then he should probably do so without the knight on c3. If
the bishop is going to go to b2, then the knight is usually better off on d2.
In the game, Akobian tried to justify the development of his knight to c3 by
playing e3-e4 and Be3. However, he soon found out his dark squares were
critically weak after} Bxc5 12. h3 (12. e4 $2 Ng4 13. Rf1 Nd4 $19 {0-1 (13)
Gubsky,E (2303)-Saulin,D (2376) Sochi 2018}) (12. Bd2 Rd8 {transposes to 10.
dxc5}) 12... b6 13. e4 (13. b3 Bb7 14. Bb2 Na5 $11 {is an even more favorable
version for Black than the one seen after 10.dxc5}) 13... Nd7 14. Be3 Bxe3 15.
Qxe3 Nb4 16. Qe2 Bb7 17. Rac1 Nc5 $15 {0-1 (61) Akobian,V (2662)-Kovalyov,A  
(2641) Tbilisi 2017}) 11... Rd8 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gd8d5]} (11... b6 $6 12. d5 $1
exd5 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Bxd5 Bf6 (14... Bb7 15. Bc3) 15. Bc3 Bxc3 16. bxc3 Bb7
17. Rab1 $14) 12. Be1 (12. Rac1 cxd4 13. exd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Rxd4 $15) 12...
cxd4 (12... Nb4 $5 13. Rac1 b6 $13 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gb4d5,Gf6d5]}) (12... b6
13. d5 exd5 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Bxd5 Bb7 16. Bc3 $14) 13. exd4 {with the bishop
on e1 this looks like a good IQP for black} Nb4 14. Rac1 (14. Ne5 Bd7 15. Rac1
Rac8 (15... Be8 $5) (15... Qd6 $5) 16. Bb3 Qb8 17. Bd2 Be8 $11 {0-1 (29)
Dadonov,R-Yuferev,O (2294) Moscow 2008}) 14... Qd6 15. Ng5 (15. Ne5 Bd7 16. f3
Be8 17. Bf2 Rac8 $15 {0-1 (44) Faizrakhmanov,R (2422)-Timofeev,A (2601) Palic
2016}) 15... Bd7 16. Nge4 Qf4 17. Nxf6+ Qxf6 18. d5 exd5 19. Rxd5 Bc6 20. Ne4
Qg6 21. Rxd8+ Rxd8 22. Ng3 Bf8 23. b3 {and here a draw was prematurely agreed
to in the game ½-½ Tisdall,J (2455)-Binham,T (2370) Helsinki 1986. Black
could have continued} Nd3 24. Bxd3 Rxd3 $15 *

