1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 a6 6. a4 c5 7. O-O Nc6 8. Qe2
Qc7 9. Rd1 {This is a more flexible move than 9.Nc3. The main point is that
white intends to take on c5 and develop the bishop to b2. In such cases the
white knight is better off on d2 than on c3} Be7 10. dxc5 {White intends to
put the bishop on b2, so it makes sense to open up the diagonal with gain of
tempo once the bishop has moved to e7} (10. Nc3 {- transposes to 9.Nc3}) ({
White can also try to maintain the tension, but this will likely transpose to
the game while allowing Black some interesting possibilities along the way} 10.
b3 O-O 11. Bb2 b6 12. Nbd2 Bb7 13. Rac1 Rfd8 14. dxc5 bxc5 $5 $13 {[%csl Ga5,
Rb3,Gb4][%cal Ga8b8,Gb8b3] this move is not normally available to Black and in
this case deserves serious consideration. White's queenside weaknesses are
exposed and a powerful outpost on b4 is created} (14... Bxc5 {transposes to
the mianline})) 10... Bxc5 11. b3 O-O 12. Bb2 b6 13. Nbd2 ({Black does not
need to fear the doubling of his pawns. White's dark/squared bishop is such an
important piece that is amply compensated the weakening of the structure. For
example, after} 13. Bxf6 $6 gxf6 14. Nc3 Be7 15. Rac1 Bb7 (15... Ne5 $2 16. Bd5
$1 $18 {1-0 (40) Guo,Q (2435)-Galliamova,A (2459) Astana 2013}) 16. Ne4 Rfd8
17. Bd3 Qb8 18. Ng3 Nb4 19. Bb1 Rxd1+ 20. Rxd1 Qf8 21. Be4 (21. Nh5 Nd5 $11) (
21. Nd4 Rd8 22. Qh5 Qg7 $11) 21... Bxe4 (21... Nd5 22. Nd4 Rc8 23. Qh5) 22.
Nxe4 Rd8 $11) 13... Bb7 14. Rac1 {This is an important position in the
variation. Black will relocate the queen to e7 and trade off as many rooks as
possible along the d-file. Once this is done, he may start putting pressure on
White's queenside with moves like ...Nb4. However, I would not rush to put the
knight on b4 as this will surrender control over e5 (as seen in
Anand-Ponomariov), but most importantly it will deprive us of the key
defensive manoeuvre... Qe7 followed by ...Ba3} Rfd8 (14... Nb4 $6 {[%csl Gb2]
[%cal Gb2h8]} 15. Ng5 Qe7 16. Ndf3 h6 17. Nh3 Rfd8 18. Nf4 Rxd1+ 19. Rxd1 Rd8
20. Rxd8+ Qxd8 21. Ne5 $14 {1-0 (46) Anand,V (2755)-Ponomariov,R (2743) Mainz
2002}) (14... Qe7 $5 {[%cal Gc5a3,Gf8d8]}) 15. Bd3 ({Black should constantly
be on the lookout for this pivoting manoeuvre. The white knight is coming to
e4 and the queen will swing over to the kingside. Such positions can give
White a powerful initiative} 15. Ng5 $5 Qe7 $1 {this is a key part of Black's
setup and the main way we will neutralize White's kingside ambitions. In part,
this is due to the additional support we provide for the knight on f6, but
mainly thanks to the idea of trading off dark/squared bishops with ...Ba3.
Therefore, it should not be delayed any longer} 16. Bd3 (16. Nge4 Nxe4 17. Nxe4
Ba3 $11) 16... h6 17. Nge4 Nxe4 18. Nxe4 Ba3 $11) 15... Qe7 16. h3 (16. Nc4 {
White has prevented us from trading off the dark-squared bishops, but now he
will not be able to put the knight on e4. In such cases, White will find it
difficult to develop a kingside attack.} a5 (16... Nb4 $5 17. Bb1 Rxd1+ 18.
Rxd1 Rd8 $11) 17. Ng5 h6 18. Ne4 Nxe4 19. Bxe4 Rxd1+ 20. Rxd1 Rd8 {1/2-1/2 (41)
Hu,B (2264)-Reshef,O (2476) New York USA 2019}) 16... h6 (16... Ba3 $6 17. Bxa3
Qxa3 18. Nc4 Qb4 19. e4 $36 {[%cal Ge4e5]}) 17. Ne4 (17. e4 $2 Nh5 $15 {
[%cal Gh5f4]}) (17. Nc4 Nb4 18. Bb1 Rxd1+ 19. Rxd1 Rd8 $11 {1/2-1/2 (40)
Peralta,F (2556)-Illescas Cordoba, M (2605) Barcelona 2018}) 17... Nxe4 18.
Bxe4 Rac8 19. Rxd8+ Rxd8 20. Ba1 ({White should not get greedy with} 20. Bxc6
$6 Bxc6 21. Qxa6 Bxf3 22. gxf3 Qg5+ 23. Kf1 Qf5 24. Kg2 Rd2 $44 (24... Qg5+ $11
)) 20... Nb4 21. Qb2 f6 22. Bxb7 Qxb7 $11 {Black has been forced to slightly
weaken his kingside, but control over the d-file and White's tender queenside
offset this minor problem.} *

