{[%evp 0,89,19,31,19,0,14,25,45,-23,18,-26,-9,-24,-19,3,7,-77,-10,-36,16,26,17,
-49,-26,-31,0,0,0,0,0,0,33,0,0,43,39,33,44,26,44,16,22,22,41,25,19,13,40,38,42,
21,18,10,20,26,6,-1,1,-6,0,0,0,0,-10,-15,-13,-40,-44,-43,-42,-41,-22,-37,-22,
-18,-36,-59,-54,-54,-51,-51,-51,-51,-51,-51,-51,-51,-51,-51,-51,-51]} 1. d4 d5
2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qa4+ {This move was always considered slightly
dubious but shouldn't be underestimated.} Nc6 5. Qxc4 (5. Nc3 {It is
interesting but can be met by} Nd5 6. Qxc4 (6. e4 Nb6 7. Qd1 Bg4 8. d5 Ne5 9.
Bf4 Ng6 {reminds of the position in line 3.e4 Nc6, but Black is much ahead of
time and can get a good position after:} 10. Bg3 e5 11. dxe6 Qxd1+ 12. Rxd1
fxe6 {0-1 (37) Dreev,A (2633)-Krush,I (2464) Gausdal 2007}) (6. Ne5 Nb6 7. Nxc6
Qd6 8. Qa5 (8. Qc2 Qxc6 9. e4 e5 10. dxe5 Be6 {[%cal Re8c8] I can't see any
problems for Black, he is ready to castle long with a very active position})
8... Qxc6 9. e4 e6 {White needs to work hard to prove enough compensation})
6... Nb6 7. Qb5 a6 8. Qd3 e5 9. Nxe5 Qxd4 10. Nxc6 Qxd3 11. exd3 bxc6 {with a
level endgame ½- (25) ½ (25) Ivanchuk,V (2786)-Dominguez Perez,L (2719)
Almaty 2008}) (5. e3 Nd7 6. Bxc4 {against 5.e3, I decided to opt for the line
suggested by GM Hungaski} (6. Qxc4 e5 7. dxe5 Ndxe5 8. Nxe5 Nxe5 9. Qb5+ Nd7)
6... Nb6 7. Qc2 Nxc4 8. Qxc4 Be6 $11) 5... e5 {very interesting sacrifice,
suggested by Delchev in his book and recently employed by the biggest expert
in QGA - Lenier Dominguez} 6. Nxe5 (6. dxe5 $6 Be6 7. Qa4 Nd7 8. Nc3 $2 (8. Bd2
Nc5 9. Qd1 Qd7 {[%cal Re8c8,Re6g4] with a full compensation for the pawn}) 8...
Nc5 9. Qd1 Qxd1+ 10. Kxd1 O-O-O+ 11. Bd2 g6 $17 {Black's initiative is
overwhelming 0-1 (24) Ahlander,B (2419)-Brynell,S (2506) Skara 2002}) 6... Nxe5
7. dxe5 Ng4 {Black is playing in the spirit of the Budapest Gambit} 8. Bf4 c6
9. e3 g5 10. Bg3 Qa5+ 11. Nd2 (11. Nc3 {After this Black has a nice trick} Nxe5
$1 12. Qe4 Bg7 $1 13. f4 $4 (13. Be2 O-O {and only Black can fight for an
advantage here}) 13... Bf5 $19 {and White's queen is trapped}) 11... Be6 12.
Qc2 O-O-O 13. O-O-O Bb4 {Black has a very active play. The engine says 0.00,
if you are interested, you can investigate further. I decided to stop here
because both sides have multiple choices. In any case idea 6...e5 is very
interesting in fresh.} 14. a3 Bxd2+ 15. Rxd2 Bb3 16. Qf5+ Be6 17. Qc2 Bb3 18.
Qc3 $11 Qxc3+ 19. bxc3 Rxd2 20. Kxd2 Rd8+ 21. Ke2 Rd5 22. h4 Bc4+ 23. Kf3 Nxe5+
24. Bxe5 Bxf1 25. Bd4 Rf5+ 26. Kg3 gxh4+ 27. Rxh4 Rg5+ 28. Rg4 Rxg4+ 29. Kxg4
Bxg2 30. Bxa7 b5 31. Kg5 Kd7 32. Kh6 Be4 33. f3 Bxf3 34. Kxh7 Ke6 35. Kg7 f5
36. Kf8 Kd5 37. Ke7 Kc4 38. Kd6 Kxc3 39. Bb6 Kb3 40. Bc5 Be4 41. Ke5 Kc4 42.
Kd6 Kb3 43. Ke5 Kc4 44. Kd6 Kb3 45. Ke5 {½-½ (45) Rapport,R (2763)-Dominguez
Perez,L (2758) Saint Louis 2021} *

