{[%evp 0,38,29,14,20,28,28,4,25,14,21,8,11,-17,-4,-11,65,65,77,58,58,15,4,-43,
-22,-46,-12,-12,0,0,0,0,0,-24,-31,-10,-10,-18,-20,-20,-93] In this game I will
analyze some of the rare lines against QGA. GM Hungaski wonderfully analyzed
them in his database for Modern Chess. So I just re-check his analyses with
the newest engines and also add some fresh games, but more or less, the
evaluation of those lines remains the same.} 1. Nf3 d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 dxc4 4.
Nc3 {This line is very dangerous and underestimated, in my opinion.} a6 5. e4 (
5. a4 $6 {I face this move very often in blitz games. Black is fighting for an
advantage here.} Nc6 6. e4 (6. a5 e6 $15 {[%cal Rf8b4]}) (6. e3 Na5 {[%cal
Rc7c5]}) 6... Bg4 7. Be3 e5 8. d5 Na5 $15) (5. e3 {The simplest is to
transpose to our main line after:} e6 6. Bxc4 c5 7. O-O Nc6) 5... b5 6. e5 Nd5
7. a4 e6 8. axb5 Bb4 (8... Nb6 {is the old main line, but White seems to be
better after:} 9. Be3 axb5 (9... Bb7 10. bxa6 Rxa6 11. Rxa6 Nxa6 12. Be2 Be7
13. Nd2 $14) 10. Rxa8 Nxa8 11. Nxb5 $14) {White has three possible
continuations here: 9.Qc2, 9.Qd2, 9.Bd2. White's main idea in this line is to
use the absence of Black knights from the kingside and to organize an attack
by means of transferring the queen to the kingside. Usually via e4 or f4
squares.} 9. Qc2 (9. Bd2 {This looks like the most logical move, but is very
slow and also blocks the queen from going to f4, via d2-square.} Nb6 {Black is
continuing as always, protecting the pawn on c4.} 10. Be2 Bb7 11. O-O O-O 12.
bxa6 Rxa6 13. Rc1 (13. Rxa6 Nxa6 14. Be3 c5 {This is the key idea for Black in
this structure, Black has no problems at all. For more details, you can check
the analyses of GM Hungasky which I include in the file as well.}) 13... N8d7
14. Ng5 h6 15. Nh3 c5 $19 {Black is already almost winning here. 0-1 (38)
Salem,A (2642)-Caruana,F (2811) Chess.com INT 2018}) (9. Qd2 {With the idea
Qd2-f4} Nb6 {In the recent game Saleh opts for} 10. bxa6 (10. Be2 {Is the old
theory and Black is doing fine after:} Bb7 11. bxa6 Rxa6 12. Rxa6 Nxa6 13. O-O
O-O 14. Qf4 f5 $6 (14... c5 {again Black should opt for the typical:}) 15. exf6
$14 {1-0 (43) Grandelius,N (2643)-Edouard,R (2648) Grosseto Prugna 2016}) 10...
Rxa6 11. Rxa6 Bxa6 12. Be2 Nc6 13. O-O O-O 14. Qf4 Ne7 15. Qg4 Nf5 (15... Bb7 {
is another possibility to exchange the knight when it comes to e4} 16. Ne4 Bxe4
17. Qxe4 Qd5 18. Qc2 Nf5 $15) 16. Ne4 Be7 17. Rd1 Bb7 18. Nc5 $6 (18. Ng3 Qd7
$1) 18... Bc6 $15 {0-1 (53) Salem,A (2684)-Aronian, L (2775) Chess.com INT 2022
}) 9... Nb6 {Black should protect the c4-pawn.} 10. Qe4 Qd5 $1 11. Qg4 axb5 12.
Rxa8 Qxa8 {This is a very force line, where Black should be well prepared. We
sacrificed the pawn on g7, but opted for a counterplay against the White king.}
13. Qxg7 (13. Be2 $5 {White can avoid the forced draw, but is risking to be
worse after:} g6 $1 14. O-O Bxc3 15. bxc3 h6 16. Qh3 (16. Qf4 N8d7 $17) 16...
Qa2 17. Bd1 Qb1 {0-1 (31) Gormally,D (2504) -Edouard,R (2632) England 2016})
13... Bxc3+ 14. bxc3 Qa1 15. Qxh8+ Kd7 16. Be2 $6 (16. Kd1 Qa4+ $1 (16... Nd5 {
Is not very accurate because White can continue the game by means of:} 17. Qxh7
Nxc3+ 18. Kd2 Nc6 19. Qc2 $14 (19. Qxf7+ $5 $16)) 17. Ke2 $2 (17. Kd2 Qa2+ $11)
(17. Ke1 $11 Qa1) 17... Qc2+ 18. Bd2 Nd5 {and Black is the one who is winning
here.}) 16... Qxc1+ 17. Bd1 Qxc3+ 18. Nd2 Nc6 $1 {[%mdl 2048]} 19. Qxh7 Nxd4 (
19... Nd5 $1 20. Qxf7+ Nce7 $17) 20. Qxf7+ Kc6 21. Qf4 (21. h4 {was more
accurate, but it is very easy to go wrong in such a complicated position.} b4
22. h5 b3 {and it seems that Black is faster}) 21... Nd5 22. Qe4 Kc5 (22... Ba6
$1 {[%cal Rb5b4,Rb4b3,Rb3b2]}) 23. h4 Bb7 (23... Nb4 $1 24. Qe3 Nd3+ $17) 24.
h5 Nb4 (24... Nb3 25. Bxb3 cxb3) 25. O-O $1 {Now the roles are turned and
Black should fight for equality} Qxd2 26. Qxb7 Nd5 27. h6 $1 c3 $1 (27... Qxh6
{loses on a spot} 28. Qa7+ Nb6 29. Qxc7+ $18) 28. h7 Qh6 29. Qa7+ Kc4 30. Bg4
$2 (30. Qa2+ Kc5 31. Qa7+ $11) 30... c2 31. Qa2+ Kb4 (31... Kd3 $1 $19) 32.
Qb2+ Kc4 33. Re1 $5 Nf4 $4 {[%mdl 8192] This move loses on a spot} (33... Qxh7
34. Be2+ Kc5 $1 $19) 34. h8=Q $1 Qxh8 35. Re4 c5 36. Rxf4 Qxe5 37. Qxc2+ Kd5
38. Qd2 c4 39. Rxd4+ Qxd4 40. Bxe6+ Kc5 41. Qxd4+ Kxd4 42. g4 Ke5 43. Bf7 Kf4
44. f3 1-0

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4.Nc3 & 8...Bb4"]
[Black "9.Qd2"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D24"]
[Annotator "GM Arnaudov&GM Hungaski"]
[PlyCount "44"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 $5 {I have long believed this to be one
of White's most underrated (and dangerous) options against the QGA. The
position resembles that of the Tolush Gambit against the Slav (1.d4 d5 2.c4 c6
3.Nf3 Nf6 4.Nc3 dxc4 5.e4 b5), where Black can run into a lot of trouble is he
desperately tries to cling to his extra pawn. Black's most effective strategy
seems to be to return the material and secure some positional trumps instead.
Mainly, the d5-square. Therefore, Black should continue} a6 5. e4 (5. a4 $6 {
I'm surprised at how many times I have faced this move. I think Black is
already considerably better after} Nc6 $1 {Now that White has weakened his
queenside, the knight is heading for the a5-square should White play e2-e3 or
put pressure on d4 should White play e2-e4.} 6. e4 (6. e3 $6 Na5 7. Ne5 Be6 8.
Be2 c5 $17 {Now Black can undouble his pawns at will and easily defend the c4/
pawn by means of ...Qc7 and ...Rc8. Moreover, the bishop will now be developed
via g7: 0-1 (34) Teychene, J (2152)-Karpatchev, A (2421) Toulon 2001}) 6... Bg4
7. Be3 (7. d5 Ne5 8. Qd4 Nxf3+ 9. gxf3 Bxf3 10. Rg1 e5 $1 $15 {0-1 (29)
Santiago, Y (2477)-Hungaski, R (2504) Buenos Aires 2017}) 7... Bxf3 8. gxf3 Na5
$1 {After this move I don't see a way for White to recover the pawn} 9. Qc2 e6
10. Rg1 c6 11. Rd1 Qc7 12. f4 g6 13. Bh3 Rd8 14. Rg3 b5 15. d5 exd5 16. Bd4 Bg7
17. axb5 axb5 18. exd5 O-O $17 {0-1 (32) Trichkov,V (2314)-Cernousek,L (2450)
Czech Republic 2017}) (5. e3 e6 6. Bxc4 b5 {[%csl Rc3] transposes to our main
line where White has prematurely developed the knight to c3. Therefore, all
the critical lines based on the a2-a4 pawn break will be much weaker}) 5... b5
6. e5 Nd5 7. a4 e6 (7... Bb7 $6 8. e6 $36) (7... c6 $6 8. axb5 Nxc3 9. bxc3
cxb5 10. Ng5 $36) 8. axb5 {Black has committed to give back the pawn, but he
has two different ways of doing this: After reviewing the lines and games
mentioned below, I came to appreciate why Delchev (in his excellent book
"Understanding the Queen's Gambit Accepted", 2005) recommends} Bb4 $1 {The
idea of this move is to force White to defend the knight on c3 and thanks to
this prevent the queen sortie to the kingside. If the bishop must go to d2,
then Kramnik's manoeuvre Be3, Nd2 and Qg4 will no longer be possible} (8... Nb6
$6 {The problem with this move is that Black is not able to create enough
pressure on the queenside to prevent White from launching an attack on the
other flank.} 9. Be3 $1 (9. Be2 Bb7 10. bxa6 Rxa6 11. Rxa6 Nxa6 12. O-O Be7 13.
Be3 O-O 14. Nd2 Qa8 $132 {is another critical position, but it seems that
Black is holding on as shown in the game: 0-1 (95) Ikonnikov, V (2587)-Mannion,
S (2346) Port Erin 2006}) 9... axb5 (9... Bb4 $6 10. Nd2 {with the idea to
continue with Qg4} axb5 11. Rxa8 Nxa8 12. Qg4 $36 {1-0 (49) Kramnik,V (2765)
-Kortschnoj,V (2635) Budapest 1996}) (9... Bb7 10. bxa6 Rxa6 11. Rxa6 Nxa6 12.
Be2 Be7 13. Nd2 $14 {1-0 (64) Yevseev,D (2520)-Semcesen,D (2460) Lvov 2009})
10. Rxa8 Nxa8 11. Nxb5 Nb6 12. Be2 Be7 13. O-O O-O 14. Qc2 $14 {1/2-1/2 (31)
Markus,R (2609)-Stevic,H (2613) Bol 2014}) 9. Qd2 {The point of 4.Nc3 is
centered around the idea of quickly transfering the queen over to the kingside.
In such cases, White's initiative on the kingside should not be underestimated.
For a time it appeared that the move 8...Bb4 put an end to this idea but after
9.Qd2!? White's idea once again comes to life. Nevertheless, Black should be
able to keep the balance with 12...c5!N. It's worth pointing out that Black
should not be over-reliant on the weakness of the d5-square since he too has
some serious structural weaknesses on the queenside.} Nb6 10. Be2 Bb7 11. bxa6
Rxa6 12. Rxa6 Nxa6 13. O-O O-O 14. Qf4 {This is the whole point of 9. Qd2. The
queen finds an original way of getting to the kingside} c5 $1 {Immediately
creating pressure on d4 and undoubling the pawns. Black should not delay this
move} (14... Be7 $6 15. Qg4 Kh8 16. Rd1 Nb4 17. Ne4 N4d5 18. Nfg5 $36 {1-0 (40)
Cordes,H (2231)-Mannion,S (2335) Hersonissos 2017}) (14... f5 $6 15. exf6 Qxf6
16. Qg4 $36 {1-0 (43) Grandelius,N (2643)-Edouard,R (2648) Grosseto Prugna 2016
}) (14... f6 $6 15. Qg3 $36) 15. dxc5 (15. Nb5 Bxf3 $5 (15... cxd4 16. Nbxd4
Qd5 17. Rd1 Qe4 $11) 16. Bxf3 cxd4 17. Nxd4 Bc5 18. Rd1 Nb4 {all the black
pieces join the game and White's bishop pair only makes his position
symbolically better. Black is fine} 19. Nc6 (19. Nxe6 Qxd1+ 20. Bxd1 fxe6 $132)
19... Qc7 20. Nxb4 Bxb4 21. Be3 Bc5 $11) (15. Qg3 $6 cxd4 16. Bh6 g6 17. Bxf8
Bxf8 $17) (15. Qg4 $6 Bxf3 16. Bxf3 cxd4 17. Bh6 g6 18. Ne4 (18. Bxf8 Bxf8 $44)
18... Nd7 19. Bxf8 Bxf8 $44) 15... Nxc5 16. Be3 (16. Rd1 Qb8 17. Bxc4 Bxf3 18.
gxf3 Bxc3 19. bxc3 Rc8 20. Ba2 Nbd7 21. Be3 Nxe5 $11 {Black is at least equal})
(16. Qg3 Ne4 (16... Bxc3 17. Bh6 Bxe5 18. Nxe5 Qf6 19. Bg5 Qf5 20. Bh6 Qf6 $11)
17. Nxe4 Bxe4 18. Rd1 Qc7 $13) 16... Qc7 (16... Bxf3 17. Qxf3 Nd3 18. Qg3 Qc7
19. Ne4 Nd7 20. Bd4 Bc5 21. Nxc5 N7xc5 $132 {the two knights have nothing to
fear from the bishops}) (16... Qb8 $5) 17. Nb5 Qb8 18. Qg3 Bxf3 19. gxf3 (19.
Bxf3 $2 Nbd7 $17 {[%csl Rb5,Re5]}) (19. Qxf3 Qxe5 $15) 19... Ncd7 20. f4 Nd5 (
20... Rc8 $5 {[%cal Gb6d5]}) 21. Bxc4 Nxe3 22. fxe3 Bc5 $44 {[%csl Rb2,Re3,Rg1]
White has won a pawn, but his king is exposed (exacerbated by the presence of
opposite colored bishops) and has several vulnerable pawns} *

