1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 ({It will be useful to compare our line with the following
game} 2... e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 dxc4 5. Qa4+ Nc6 6. Qxc4 Nd7 7. Bg2 Nb6 8. Qb5
a6 9. Qd3 e5 10. Nxe5 Nb4 11. Qd1 Qxd4 12. Qxd4 Nc2+ 13. Kd1 Nxd4 14. Be3 Nf5
15. Bxb6 cxb6 16. Nc3 $16 {1-0 (47) Kramnik,V (2772) -Naiditsch,A (2654)
Dortmund 2007}) 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qa4+ $5 {After Kramnik revided the Catalan some
15 years ago, people began to appreciate the power of the bishop on g2 and
began looking for ways to incorporate the fianchetto to as many lines in their
repertoire as possible. 4.Qa4 is White's attempt at doing this against the QGA.
However, as you will see below White falls short. But in order to understand
the position, you must be familiar with the game Kramnik-Naiditsch. Even
though that game was a standard Catalan, the ideas are analogous. However,
we'll see that Black has an extra tempo here (by not playing ...e7-e6) and
this turns out to have a major impact on the position (since black's idea is
to carry out the ...e7-e5 pawn break). The game usually continues:} Nc6 (4...
c6 5. Qxc4 {transposes to the 4.Qb3/4.Qc2 variation of the Slav Defense} Bg4 (
5... Bf5)) 5. Qxc4 $6 {Playing this position "Catalan style" is a bad idea.
Black can make effective use of the extra tempo} Nd7 ({Delchev recommends a
very interesting (and thematic) pawn sacrifice after} 5... e5 $5 6. Nxe5 (6.
dxe5 $6 Be6 7. Qa4 Nd7 8. Nc3 Nc5 9. Qd1 Qxd1+ 10. Kxd1 O-O-O+ 11. Bd2 g6 $15 {
0-1 (24) Ahlander,B (2419)-Brynell,S (2506) Skara 2002}) 6... Nxe5 7. dxe5 Ng4
$44) 6. g3 Nb6 7. Qb5 {This was Kramnik's idea, in order to weaken Black's
control over the b6-square.} (7. Qd3 e5 $1 {Black is just a tempo up compared
to the Catalan.} 8. Nxe5 Nb4 9. Qd1 Qxd4 10. Qxd4 Nc2+ 11. Kd1 Nxd4 12. Be3 Nf5
13. Bxb6 axb6 $15 {Black is just better}) 7... a6 8. Qd3 e5 9. Nxe5 Nb4 10. Qd1
Qxd4 11. Qxd4 Nc2+ 12. Kd1 Nxd4 13. Be3 ({In one of my games, my opponent tried
} 13. e3 Nb5 14. a4 Nd6 15. a5 Nd7 16. Nxd7 Bxd7 17. Bg2 g6 18. Nc3 Bg7 19. Ke2
O-O-O 20. Rd1 Rhe8 $15 {And White failed to equalize 0-1 (33) Alonso,S (2510)
-Hungaski,R (2519) Buenos Aires Blitz 2018}) (13. Bg2 {Is also not giving
White any advantage.} f6 14. Nf3 Nc6 15. Nc3 (15. Bf4 Nd5 $15) 15... Bf5 $15)
13... Be6 $1 {[%csl Rf1] This is the key difference with the Kramnik game.
Black is up a tempo (by playing ...e7-e5 in one move) and that means White has
not had time to develop the bishop to g2. Otherwise, in this position, White
could have played Bxb7} 14. Bxd4 (14. Bg2 O-O-O $17 {looks horrible for White})
14... O-O-O 15. e3 c5 $15 {The position will open up, Black will regain his
pawn and maintain the bishop pair and a better pawn structure} *

