1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Qa4+ Nc6 5. e3 Nd7 $1 {[%cal Ge7e5] In the 5.
Nc3 line it was important for the knight to go to d5 since it gave Black the
additional option of playing ...Ndb4. Here it is important that the knight go
to d7, since this will give Black the option of playing the ...e5 pawn break.
These two factors (...Nb4 and ...e5) are the subtleties that will determine
whether . ..Nd7 or ...Nd5 is called for. However, if the knight is headed to
b6 then it won't make a difference} (5... Nd5 6. Qxc4 (6. Ne5 {is not
dangerous for Black.} Nb6 7. Nxc6 Qd6 8. Qc2 Qxc6 $15) 6... Nb6 7. Qc2 $14 {
With a slight advantage for White.}) 6. Qxc4 (6. Bxc4 {giving up the
light-squared bishop is not a good idea.} Nb6 7. Qb3 Nxc4 8. Qxc4 Be6 $1 {
Black takes the time to dislodge the white queen from c4. After it retreats
there will be no d4-d5} (8... Bg4 $6 9. d5 Bxf3 10. gxf3 $14) 9. Qc2 (9. Qb5 $6
{is just waste of time} a6 $1 {the pawn is untouchable} 10. Qxb7 $4 Bd5 $17) (
9. Qa4 {is not giving White any advantage} Bd5 10. Nc3 Bxf3 11. gxf3 e6 $11)
9... Bg4 10. Nbd2 e6 11. O-O Bd6 12. b3 O-O 13. Bb2 Nb4 14. Qc4 Nd5 $11 {
Black has nothing to worry about 0-1 (60) Lechtynsky,J (2470)-Balashov,Y (2555)
Trnava 1988}) 6... e5 7. dxe5 ({Perhaps it is most accurate to play} 7. Nxe5
Ndxe5 8. dxe5 Nxe5 {transposing to the main line while avoiding Black's
alternative 7...Nc5!?}) 7... Ndxe5 (7... Nc5 $5 8. Bd2 Be6 9. Qc2 Qd7 10. Bc3
Bf5 11. Qd1 Nd3+ 12. Bxd3 Bxd3 $44) 8. Nxe5 Nxe5 {White must play with caution
since Black will continue to develop his pieces at the expense of the white
queen} 9. Qb5+ ({The big problem for White in this line is finding a good
place for the queen. Another alternative is} 9. Qe4 Bd6 10. Be2 (10. f4 f5 $15)
10... O-O 11. O-O Re8 12. Qc2 Qh4 13. f4 Ng4 14. Bxg4 Bxg4 $15 {0-1 (57)
Zietlow,T (2065) -Raetsky,A (2440) Germany 1999}) 9... Nd7 10. Bd2 {It's not
entirely clear to me that putting the bishop on c3 is a good idea. In fact, it
seems vulnerable to attack in many variations} ({It's probably safest for
White to play} 10. Be2 c6 11. Qc4 Bd6 (11... Nf6 $5 12. O-O Bd6 13. Rd1 Qc7 14.
h3 Bf5 $11 {also looks quite promising for Black. The queen on c4 is misplaced
and will have difficulties finding a good square}) 12. Qe4+ Be7 13. O-O Nf6 14.
Qc2 O-O 15. b3 Qd5 16. Bb2 Bf5 17. Qc1 Rfd8 $11 {Black's position is optically
better, but probably not enough to break the balance. A draw was soon agreed
in the game ½-½ (26) Andersson,U (2610) -Timman,J (2600) Tilburg 1982}) 10...
Be7 11. Bc3 O-O ({In one of my games I played the careless} 11... Bf6 $6 12.
Bxf6 Qxf6 13. Qb4 $1 {allowing White to halt my development and forcing me to
trade queens. This effectively kills any chance Black might have had at
developing an initiative based on his lead in development} Qe7 14. Qxe7+ Kxe7
$11 {1/2-1/2 (57) Santiago, Y (2414)-Hungaski, R (2467) Buenos Aires 2015}) 12.
Nd2 (12. Be2 {is possible, but Black's position remains preferable after:} Nc5
({or} 12... c6 13. Qa4 Nc5 14. Qc2 Qd5 15. O-O Bf5 $15) 13. O-O c6 14. Qc4 Qd6
15. Rd1 Qg6 16. Bb4 Be6 17. Qc1 Nb3 18. axb3 Bxb4 $15 {Black's position is
very good due to his bishop pair and better structure.}) 12... c6 13. Qb3 a5 $1
{White has exposed too many of his pieces on the queenside and the best way of
taking advantage of them is by pursuing them with pawns} (13... Nc5 {is
possible but doesn't lead to an advantage.} 14. Qc2 Qd5 15. e4 Qh5 16. Be2 Bg4
17. Bxg4 Qxg4 18. O-O Rfd8 19. f3 Qf4 20. Nb3 Ne6 $11) (13... Nb6 $5 14. Be2
Be6 15. Qc2 Nd5 $15) 14. Be2 b5 15. a3 (15. O-O $2 {is just bad} b4 $1 16. Bd4
c5 $19) 15... Ba6 16. Nf3 (16. O-O b4 17. Bxa6 Nc5 18. Qc2 bxc3 $19 {and Black
is winning a piece}) 16... Qb6 17. Nd4 (17. O-O $2 b4 $17) 17... Nc5 18. Qc2 b4
