1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4 e5 {Long time ago, 3.e4 was considered not a very
good move, because 3...e5 equalized easily. Things have changed, and 3.e4 is
considered the most principled reply after 2...dxc4} 4. Nf3 exd4 5. Bxc4 Bb4+
6. Nbd2 Nc6 7. O-O Nf6 8. e5 Nd5 9. Nb3 Nb6 10. Bb5 Bd7 11. Qe2 $6 {This is
the most dangerous setup for Black, but White chooses a sideline. Later in the
lecture, we will see the main moves in the position} O-O {The general rule is
that White needs to play dynamic. If Black manages to castle, he is completely
out of danger. Black has no weaknesses, no bad pieces, etc...} 12. Rd1 Re8 (
12... Qc8 13. Bf4 Rd8) 13. Bf4 f6 14. Nbxd4 (14. e6 Rxe6 15. Qc2 Bd6 $1 (15...
Nd5 16. Bg3 Bf8 (16... Bd6) 17. Bd3 g6 18. Nbxd4 Nxd4 19. Nxd4 Re7 20. Qb3 c6)
16. Nbxd4 Nxd4 17. Nxd4 Re7 18. Bxd6 cxd6 19. Bd3 g6 20. a4 (20. Bxg6) (20. h4
Be8 21. h5 Rc8) 20... d5 21. a5 Rc8 22. Qb3 Nc4 23. Qxb7 Bg4) 14... Nxe5 15.
Bxe5 (15. Nxe5 fxe5 16. Bxe5 Bd6 17. Nf3 Kh8) 15... fxe5 16. Nxe5 Bxb5 17. Qxb5
Qd5 *

