{In this game we will see some queenless positions. The rule is that they are
usually quite good for Black.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4 e5 4. Nf3 Bb4+ 5. Bd2
Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 (6. Nbxd2 exd4 7. Bxc4 Nc6 8. Nb3 (8. O-O Qf6 9. e5 {1/2-1/2 (9)
Shankland,S (2633)-Granda Zuniga,J (2674) Praia da Pipa BRA 2014 The Week in
Chess 1042 [Mark Crowther]} Qg6 10. Nb3 Bg4 11. Nc5 Nge7 12. e6 fxe6 13. Re1
Rf8 14. Be2 O-O-O 15. Nh4 Qg5 {0-1 (36) Dreev,A (2673)-Jussupow,A (2583)
Warsaw POL 2013 The Week in Chess 997 [Mark Crowther]}) 8... Bg4 9. Nbxd4 Nxd4
10. Qxd4 Qxd4 11. Nxd4 {In such positions, I always prefer Black because he
has 3 versus 2 on the queenside and can create a passed pawn easier.} Rd8 12.
Nb3 Nf6 13. f3 Bc8 14. Kf2 Ke7 15. Rad1 h5 16. Nd4 c5 17. Nf5+ Bxf5 18. exf5
Rxd1 $17 {I will show you this game until the end because it is instructive
how Black converts his advantage.} 19. Rxd1 Ne8 20. Rd5 b6 21. h4 Nd6 22. Be2
f6 23. f4 Kd7 24. a4 Kc6 25. Rd1 Kc7 26. Re1 Re8 27. Bd3 Rxe1 28. Kxe1 c4 29.
Be2 Nxf5 30. Kf2 Nxh4 31. Bxh5 Kd6 32. Bf7 Kc5 33. g4 g5 34. fxg5 fxg5 35. Ke3
a6 36. Ke4 b5 37. axb5 axb5 38. Be8 b4 39. Bf7 Ng2 40. Kf5 c3 41. Bb3 cxb2 42.
Ba2 Kd4 43. Kxg5 Ne3 44. Kh5 Nxg4 {0-1 (44) Li Chao2 (2722)-Balogh,C (2658)
Barcelona ESP 2014 The Week in Chess 1047 [Mark Crowther]}) 6... exd4 7. Nxd4 (
7. Qxd4 Nf6 $1 8. Nc3 (8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Nc3 Be6 $1 10. Ng5 Ke7 11. Nxe6 fxe6
12. Bxc4 Rd8 {Black is perfectly fine.}) 8... Be6 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. Ne5 (10.
Nd4 Nc6 11. Nxc6+ bxc6 {[%cal Ra8b8,Rb8b2,Rb8b6,Rd8e7,Rh8b8,Yf6d7,Yd7c5,Yc5d3,
Yc4b3] The triple pawns are good for Black in this line. He can use the b-file
to put pressure on b-fule. 1/2 (29)-1/2 (29) Burnier,D (2347)-Donchenko,A 
(2477) Biel SUI 2013 The Week in Chess [Mark Crowther]}) 10... Nc6 (10... Nbd7
$1 11. Nxc4 c6) 11. Nxc4 Ke7 12. Ne3 Rad8 13. Be2 Nb4 (13... Rd4 14. Nc2 Rd7
$11) 14. f3 c6 15. a3 Nd3+ 16. Bxd3 Rxd3 $11 {1/2 (33)-1/2 (33) Hracek,Z (2646)
-Piorun,K (2532) Bremen GER 2015}) (7. Bxc4 c5 8. Ne5 Nh6 9. O-O Nd7 $15 {
0-1 (37) Brunner,N (2426)-Dlugy, M (2524) Pori Le Marly FRA 2013 The Week in
Chess [Mark Crowther]}) 7... Nf6 8. Nc3 O-O 9. O-O-O Qe7 10. f3 c5 11. Nde2 Nc6
12. Nf4 Be6 13. Qd6 Qxd6 14. Rxd6 Rfd8 15. Rxd8+ Rxd8 16. Nxe6 fxe6 17. Bxc4
Kf7 18. Re1 Ne5 19. Be2 g5 20. Rf1 Nc6 21. h4 h6 22. hxg5 hxg5 23. Rh1 b6 24.
b3 Kg7 25. Bc4 Kf7 26. Be2 Kg7 27. Bc4 Kf7 28. Be2 Kg7 29. Bc4 1/2-1/2

