{[%evp 0,100,27,23,15,-14,19,-18,26,39,7,21,59,53,55,43,44,40,43,39,46,29,38,4,
15,27,43,11,26,5,8,1,4,-24,-19,-17,-15,-44,7,-4,2,-26,-10,3,7,-30,-41,-23,-36,
-59,-62,-60,-55,-55,-57,-70,-74,-117,-121,-114,-107,-98,-104,-112,-106,-112,
-107,-113,-95,-115,-106,-105,-116,-111,-103,-107,-124,-107,-122,-129,-130,-156,
-156,-166,-162,-184,-188,-196,-207,-207,-208,-199,-211,-195,-228,-228,-220,
-233,-236,-263,-258,-258,-259] This model game shows one of the main
strategical ideas for Black: to occupy the d5-square with the knight and to
leave White with the "bad" dark-squared bishop} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4 Nf6
4. e5 Nd5 5. Bxc4 Nb6 6. Bd3 Nc6 7. Ne2 Bg4 8. f3 Bh5 9. Nbc3 e6 10. Be3 Bg6 {
very typical exchange} 11. Be4 Be7 12. O-O Bxe4 13. Nxe4 Nb4 14. Bf2 O-O 15. a3
N4d5 16. b4 c6 {Usually engines like White's position a lot here, but from a
human point of view Black is perfectly fine. We don't care much about the
space advantage because we have d5-square under control. Also White's
dark-squared bishop is a bad piece.} 17. Qb3 a5 18. Nc5 Nd7 $3 {very nice
decision. Hari decides to exchange White's most active piece, even in the cost
of a pawn.} 19. Nxb7 Qb6 20. Nc5 Bxc5 21. dxc5 Qa6 22. Qb2 axb4 23. axb4 Qc4 {
It is very difficult to play with White, as you see the extra pawn doesn't
matter.} 24. Rac1 Ra2 25. Rxc4 Rxb2 26. Re4 Nxb4 {Black won back the material
and went to win a nice game. Even a strong player like Ivan can't hold this
position.} 27. Rd1 Nd5 28. Rc1 Ra8 29. Bd4 Rb4 30. Ng3 h6 31. Rc2 Raa4 32. Ne2
Rc4 33. Rb2 Rab4 34. Rd2 Nxc5 35. Bxc5 Rxc5 36. Rxb4 Nxb4 37. Rd8+ Kh7 38. f4
g5 39. g3 Nd5 40. f5 exf5 41. Rd7 Kg6 42. Rd6+ Kg7 43. e6 fxe6 44. Rxe6 Rc4 45.
Rd6 h5 46. Kf2 Nf6 47. Ke3 Ng4+ 48. Kd3 Ne5+ 49. Ke3 Re4+ 50. Kf2 Ng4+ 0-1

