{[%evp 0,34,19,31,43,-8,29,20,26,-16,19,29,72,72,89,32,72,12,44,36,0,23,47,47,
50,50,50,48,43,43,49,47,53,53,60,21,21]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 dxc4 3. e4 {Against
the 3.e4 variation I believe Black's most effective plan is to force an
overexpansion of White's centre in order to quickly chip away at it. There are
basically two ways of doing this: 3...Nc6, which forced the d-pawn forward and
3...Nf6, which forces the e-pawn forward. Both moves remind me of the
underlying philosophy of the Alekhine Defense, with the major difference that
Black is not required to surrender so much space and so many tempi. In the end,
I decided on 3...Nf6 because it gives Black more straightforward play and
excellent control over the centre thanks to the powerful d5-outpost. However,
though outside the scope of this database, 3... Nc6 is a very legitimate line
that I have essayed on numerous occasions.} Nf6 4. e5 (4. Nc3 {this sideline
has long been established as good for Black. However, it is quite popular at
the club level. Black must strike immediately with} e5 $1 5. Nf3 (5. d5 {is bad
} b5 $1 6. Nxb5 (6. Bg5 Bc5 7. Nf3 Nbd7 $17 {[%cal Ga8b8]} 8. Nxb5 $2 Bxf2+ 9.
Kxf2 Nxe4+ 10. Kg1 Nxg5 $19) 6... Nxe4 7. Bxc4 (7. Qa4 c6 $1 8. dxc6 Bc5 9.
Bxc4 O-O $19) 7... Bb4+ (7... Nxf2 $5 {is also very interesting}) 8. Kf1 O-O (
8... Nxf2 $5 {is possible here as well}) 9. Qf3 Nd6 $17 {with an advantage for
Black}) (5. dxe5 $6 Qxd1+ {The endgame is in Black's favour} 6. Nxd1 (6. Kxd1
Ng4 7. Ke1 Bc5 8. Nh3 Nxe5 $17 {0-1 (19) Stojanovski,I (2258)-Stojanovic,M  
(2591) Struga 2011}) 6... Nxe4 7. Bxc4 Nc6 8. Nf3 (8. Bb5 Bb4+ 9. Ke2 Bd7 $17)
8... Bb4+ 9. Kf1 Be6 10. Bxe6 fxe6 $15 {White has managed to avoid material
losses, but his coordination and development remain poor}) (5. Be3 $6 exd4 6.
Qxd4 Qxd4 7. Bxd4 Be6 $15 {it's not clear how White will regain his pawn}) 5...
exd4 6. Qxd4 Qxd4 (6... Bd6 $5 {this is an underrated option for Black} 7. Bxc4
O-O 8. Bg5 Nc6 9. Qe3 h6 10. Bh4 Ne5 11. Nxe5 Bxe5 12. Qe2 c6 $15 {was already
more comfortable for Black in the game Timoshenko, G (2555)-Lekic, D (2370)
Tivat 1995}) 7. Nxd4 Bc5 8. Ndb5 (8. Be3 Ng4 9. Nd5 (9. Bxc4 c6 $15) 9... Na6 (
9... Nxe3 10. fxe3 Na6 11. Bxc4 c6 12. Bxa6 cxd5 13. Bb5+ Bd7 14. Bxd7+ Kxd7
15. O-O $132 {1/2-1/2 (19) Knezevic,M (2500)-Garcia Palermo,C (2520) Havana
1985}) 10. Bxc4 c6 11. Bxa6 cxd5 12. Bb5+ Bd7 13. Bxd7+ (13. Rd1 Rd8 14. exd5
Bxb5 15. Nxb5 Nxe3 16. fxe3 Bxe3 $15) 13... Kxd7 14. Rd1 (14. exd5 Rhe8 $17) (
14. a3 Rhe8 $17) (14. O-O Rhe8 $15) 14... Rhe8 15. Nf5 Nxe3 16. Nxe3 Rxe4 17.
Rxd5+ Kc6 $15) 8... Na6 9. Bf4 c6 10. Nd6+ Bxd6 11. Bxd6 Be6 {This is the
critical position for the line. White tried several moves, but Black's
position seems to be better after all of them.} 12. f3 (12. O-O-O O-O-O 13. Be2
Rhe8 14. f3 Nd7 15. Rd4 b5 16. Rhd1 Nac5 $17 {0-1 (69) Aronian,L (2786)
-Dominguez Perez,L (2719) Moscow 2009}) (12. e5 Nd7 13. Be2 f5 $5 14. O-O Nac5
15. Rad1 Kf7 16. f4 g6 17. Rd4 b5 $17 {0-1 (34) Beliavsky,A (2650)-Ponomariov,
R (2609) Enghien les Bains 1999}) 12... O-O-O 13. O-O-O Nd7 14. Be2 f6 15. Rd2
Ndc5 (15... Nac5 16. Rhd1 b5 $17) 16. e5 f5 17. Rhd1 b5 $15 {0-1 (63) Korobov,
A (2700)-Dominguez Perez,L (2732) Berlin 2015}) 4... Nd5 5. Bxc4 Bf5 $5 {
This relatively rare move is gaining popularity recently. A number of top
players have already played it. As you will see, Black's main idea is to
restrict White's choice.} ({For example, after} 5... Nb6 {besides 6.Bb3 (which
transposes to 5...Bf5), White can also play} 6. Bd3 {which is a very serious
option.}) 6. Qb3 {The most important independent option.} ({Another thematic
structure might arise after} 6. Nc3 e6 7. Bxd5 ({In case of} 7. Nge2 Nb6 {
, again we transpose to the main line.}) 7... exd5 {You should be very careful
when handling this pawn structure. In return for the bishop pair, White enjoys
a mobile kingside majority.} 8. Nge2 ({Another interesting attempt is} 8. Qf3
Be6 9. Nge2 {1-0 (28) Mamedyarov,S (2767)-So,W (2767) Chess.com INT 2019. In
my opinion, the best way to neutralize the pressure on e5 is} Nc6 10. Be3 Qd7
11. Nf4 O-O-O 12. O-O Be7 $132 {We have reached a complex position. White will
be trying to create an activity on the c-file. At the same time, Black's
counterplay is based on the advances ...g7-g5 and ...f7-f6. In my opinion,
Black is in very good shape here.}) 8... Qd7 9. Be3 Nc6 10. a3 {1-0 (54) Dubov,
D (2699)-Anton Guijarro,D (2703) chess24.com INT 2020. Black has a wide choice
of options in this position. For example, the move 10...0-0-0 is quite
playable here. I think, however, that even more attractive can be} h5 11. O-O
h4 $132 {[%cal Gc6d8,Gd8e6,Gc7c6] The idea is to restrict the mobility of
White's kingside majority. Now, Black can follow with the manoeuvre...Nd8-e6.})
({The main line} 6. Ne2 e6 7. O-O Nb6 8. Bb3 Nc6 {will be dealt with in the
next example.}) 6... c6 {This move makes the entire variation possible. It
turns out that White cannot take the b7-pawn. Therefore, the most logical move
is} 7. Ne2 ({After} 7. Qxb7 $2 {Black has} Nb6 $1 {[%cal Gf5c8] threatening ...
Bc8. After the forced sequence} 8. e6 Nxc4 9. Qxa8 Qc7 10. Nc3 Nb6 11. Bf4 Nxa8
12. Bxc7 Nxc7 $19 {Black has a winning advantage.}) ({Another important
direction is} 7. Bxd5 cxd5 8. Qxb7 Qc8 9. Qxc8+ Bxc8 10. Nc3 e6 11. f4 Nc6 12.
Nf3 Ba6 $44 {As compensation for the pawn, Black has a powerful bishop pair
and free hand on the queenside. He is already fighting for an advantage.}) ({
Another way of taking on b7 is} 7. Nc3 e6 8. Qxb7 ({After} 8. Bxd5 cxd5 9. Qxb7
Nd7 $44 {Black has more than sufficient compensation for the pawn.}) 8... Nb6
9. Be2 (9. Bb3 {0-1 (49) Can,E (2605)-Cernousek,L (2456) Sitges 2017} Be7 $17 {
[%cal Gf5d3,Gd3a6,Ge8g8,Gf7f6,Gf8f7]}) 9... Bb4 {[%cal Ge8g8,Gf7f6] It turns
out that White will need to invest some time in order to free the queen.
Meanwhile, Black can play ...0-0 followed by ...f7-f6 and ... Rf7.} 10. Nf3 O-O
11. Be3 f6 {[%cal Gf8f7]} 12. d5 {This position was reached in the game 1-0 
(46) Van Wely, L (2663)-Dorfman, J (2560) Chartres 2017. At this point, Black
should have played} exd5 13. exf6 (13. Bxb6 $2 Qxb6 14. Qxa8 $2 Nd7 $19) 13...
Qxf6 14. Bd4 Qf7 15. Qxf7+ Rxf7 16. O-O N8d7 $11 {with a balanced position.})
7... e6 8. O-O {1/2-1/2 (84) Sarana,A (2685)-Jobava,B  (2588) Europe Echecs
INT 2022} ({As always, we should consider} 8. Qxb7 $6 {Once again, Black opts
for the thematic} Nb6 9. Nd2 ({Black's idea is to answer} 9. Bb3 $2 {with} Bd3
$19 {[%cal Gd3a6]}) {Now, after} 9... Bb4 10. b3 O-O 11. a3 {Black has the
elegant} Re8 {[%cal Ge8e7] with the idea of ...Re7 on the next move.} 12. axb4
Re7 13. Ba6 Rxb7 14. Bxb7 Bd3 15. Bxa8 Nxa8 $132 {Black enjoys very good
counterplay in this complicated position.}) ({We already know that in the type
of position arising after} 8. Bxd5 cxd5 9. Qxb7 Nd7 {Black enjoys a very nice
compensation for the pawn.} 10. Qb3 Be7 11. Qg3 O-O 12. Nbc3 Qb6 13. O-O {
This position was reached in the game 1-0 (62) Greenfeld, A (2495) -Laznicka,V
(2664) Porto Carras 2018. At this point, Black should have played} f6 14. exf6
Nxf6 $44 {with enough compensation for the pawn.}) 8... Nd7 $1 $146 {In my
opinion, this new idea is Black's most precise reaction. As usual, it turns
out that the b7-pawn does not need protection. The annoying possibility of ...
N7b6 does not allow White to achieve an optimal arrangement for his pieces.} 9.
Bxd5 {Before preparing the typical advance f2-f4-f5, White wants to fix the
central structure.} ({Nothing gives} 9. Qxb7 $6 Rb8 10. Qxc6 ({Less precise is
} 10. Qxa7 N5b6 11. Bb3 Bd3 $15 {when Black is already better.}) {This move
marks the beginning of a forced sequence. After} 10... Nb4 11. Qa4 Nc2 12. Ng3
Bg6 13. Nc3 Rb4 14. Qa6 Nxa1 15. d5 {At the very least, Black can force a draw
by means of} Qb6 16. Qc8+ Qd8 17. Qa6 $11 {with repetition. Of course, you can
make your own investigation. The position is rich of possibilities.}) ({
In case of} 9. Qg3 N7b6 10. Bb3 a5 $132 {White does not manage to comfortably
arrange his pieces. He should now reckon with ...a5-a4.}) 9... cxd5 10. Ng3 Bg6
11. f4 {This is the main idea. White is preparing f4-f5. The most precise
reaction is} Bxb1 12. Rxb1 Qb6 13. Qxb6 Nxb6 14. f5 Be7 15. fxe6 fxe6 16. Nh5
Rg8 17. Nf4 Kd7 $11 {It turns out that White does not have any advantage in
this typical French Endgame.} *

